&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;***Note: The original cache
was muggled. I've place a temporary replacement to allowing for
logging, especially for those doing the CCA caches*** The Alaskan
Cache is placed in a spot that highlights a uniquely Alaskan event,
the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race. You can&amp;rsquo;t compare it to any
other competitive event in the world! A race over 1150 miles of the
roughest, most beautiful terrain Mother Nature has to offer. She
throws jagged mountain ranges, frozen river, dense forest, desolate
tundra and miles of windswept coast at the mushers and their dog
teams. Add to that temperatures far below zero, winds that can
cause a complete loss of visibility, the hazards of overflow, long
hours of darkness and treacherous climbs and side hills, and you
have the Iditarod. A race extraordinaire, a race only possible in
Alaska. From Anchorage, in south central Alaska, to Nome on the
western Bering Sea coast, each team of 12 to 16 dogs and their
musher cover over 1150 miles in 10 to 17 days. It has been called
the &amp;ldquo;Last Great Race on Earth&amp;rdquo; and it has won worldwide
acclaim and interest. For more information, visit the offical
website at &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.iditarod.com"&gt;iditarod.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thanks to Stan Hooley and the Iditarod Trail Committee for their
permission to place the cache here.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This location is the headquarters of the Iditarod Trail
Committee, the official body that runs the race. The race is ran
each year in early March. While here, be sure and visit the gift
shop/information center. If you visit in the summer, sled dog rides
are available. Please park at the west end of the parking lot.
Cache is winter accesible, but a little more challenging...&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Hangin' around</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="180211037"><groundspeak:date>2011-08-16T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="684840">mujonny</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The new cache is GC2YDRF, Cache Across America - Alaska (Version 2.0).</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="170717377"><groundspeak:date>2011-07-04T11:52:59</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="410459">AKStafford</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache has been muggled. To keep the CAA series alive, a new CAA cache has been place about 10 miles to the southwest.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="169934336"><groundspeak:date>2011-06-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="34590">SkyLidar</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">At the Iditarod HQ today, saw the cache on my GPS didnt see it was disable.. after a few minutes of searching I read the logs.  Too bad this would had been a good one.  TFTH anyway..  Great location.

Added personal Geopatch for miles

This entry was edited by lidar0101 on Wednesday, 06 August 2014 at 14:01:17 UTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="166582551"><groundspeak:date>2011-06-11T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="393180">cbassjr</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I was in Alaska on vacation from Kentucky first week of June and stopped by to (hopefully) get this one on the way from Denali to Kenai.  The Geocaching app on my iPhone was acting up so I was using a saved version of the cache listing and didn't realize it had been marked as unavailable.  Wondered aroudn for 15-20 minutes and couldn't come up with it, though I did find a suspicious spot (snapped a couple pictures) so it's good to know it wasn't just me having a very off day.  I definitely intend to visit Denali again, probably before I get the other states in this series, so I'll stop by and try for it again then.  Loved the location, though!  Fun learning about the Iditarod and wouldn't have known this was here but for the great sport of Geocaching!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="164471733"><groundspeak:date>2011-06-03T09:48:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="410459">AKStafford</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Crud. It's missing again... I'm going to have to complete reconfigure how this one is hidden.
If you are wanting to hit this cache to for the Cache Across America series, let me know and I'll make arrangements for you to get the code.
I hope to have this rehide done in a few days.
Sorry...</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.642683" lon="-111.389933"><time>2006-07-07T00:00:00</time><name>GCX0KA</name><desc>Cache Across America - Arizona by Cog&amp;Gil</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX0KA</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Arizona</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="423627" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Arizona</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Cog&amp;Gil</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="165698">Cog&amp;Gil</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Arizona</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Arizona&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Flag_of_Arizona.svg/744px-Flag_of_Arizona.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Phoenix&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Phoenix&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 6th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 16th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 48th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capital upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;The cache is located near Picacho Peak .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The peak is a landmark that was used by many explorers. It is mentioned by Father Kino in the 17th century.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A road was built in 1846 by the Mormon Battalion, on their way to California to fight a war with Mexico. The road was used later by the forty-niners and the Butterfield Overland Stage.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A civil war battle occurred here in 1862 when a Confederate scouting party was attacked by Union soldiers from California.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The "paloverde tree--saguaro cactus plant association" here is typical of the Lower Sonoran Life Zone found in much of southern Arizona.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Wildlife found here include the desert mule deer, javelina , mountain lion, bobcat, gray fox and the ubiquitous coyote.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Rattlesnakes, although not seen often do occur here, so take care as you make the short hike to the cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Picacho exit on I-10.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1355644408"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-17T14:53:29</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="45113652">IcyBird420</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Very cool!  Left trackable</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354399097"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-10T16:00:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="24065575">Meg95995</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it! Looks like there may be cases construction here soon TFTC! A Team ❤️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1355314200"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-08T17:13:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="12077">MrGigabyte</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks Cog&amp;Gil for the cache. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353858319"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-07T13:43:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3627963">WeTravelForCache</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Grabbed this one then had to get some DQ 😋 on our way to the Saguaro National Park </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1353800130"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2797318">chevyole</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Happy Easter, Tucson to Phoenix today and stopped to grab the Cache across America in the a Arizona Saguaro Forest.  Nice spot to find a cache with original log book and my kids kept asking why is 6 afraid of 7?  Thanks for keeping this going.  I wonder if it's the oldest original CaA cache?</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="34.838583" lon="-92.481933"><time>2006-10-06T00:00:00</time><name>GCYJKN</name><desc>Cache Across America - Arkansas by Gener_Lee</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCYJKN</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Arkansas</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="470727" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Arkansas</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Gener_Lee</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="425263">Gener_Lee</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="1">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Arkansas</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="200" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#96BA63"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Arkansas&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9d/Flag_of_Arkansas.svg/744px-Flag_of_Arkansas.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Little Rock&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Little Rock&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 29th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 32rd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 25th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Flower: Apple Blossom&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;State Bird: Mockingbird&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;State Gem: Diamond&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99" style="height:99px;"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; This Cache is at the base of the Second highest point in the State of Arkansas. I picked this spot because Arkansas, being the Natural State, it seemed only right to place it in one of our many state parks and this one is the most centrally located.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Pinnacle Mountain is a day-use park dedicated to environmental education, recreation, and preservation. Located just west of Little Rock, this natural environment was set aside in 1977 as Arkansas's first state park adjoining a major metropolitan area. Operating as a day-use only park, Pinnacle Mountain is dedicated to preservation, recreation, and environmental education. Park interpreters and volunteers help visitors and students understand man's relationship to the environment in the 2,000-acre park that offers a rich diversity of natural habitat.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The park's dominant natural feature, Pinnacle Mountain, rises more than a thousand feet above the Arkansas River Valley. The mountain's cone-shaped peak has long been a central Arkansas landmark. Two of the park's hiking trails lead hikers to the mountain's summit. To see the panoramic view from atop Pinnacle Mountain, visit the virtual tour featured online in the hiking section of the website featuring Arkansas's adventure state parks at: &lt;a href="http://www.adventurestateparks.com/hiking"&gt;http://www.adventurestateparks.com/hiking&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Besides being a great and beautiful location, this cache is along one of the parks easiest trails. But, for the more advanced hikers this caches also completes a 3 cache cycles of the Pinnacle Mountain consisting of (GCWP97) &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=a2881964-ee0e-4c15-ab08-a7a8073f116e"&gt;Pinnacle East&lt;/a&gt; and (GCWP8X) &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=23d824a9-54e5-4b6a-8615-0219dc00ae7b"&gt;Pinnacle West&lt;/a&gt;. These two Caches are along the two face trails up Pinnacle Mountain, and unless you plan on climbing over the mountain again the only way back to your car is along the Base Trail and past this Cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are also 3 other Caches along some of the other trails this park, for more information on Pinnacle State Park click &lt;a href="http://www.arkansasstateparks.com/pinnaclemountain"&gt;Here&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This Cache is a small ammo box hidden near to the trail. So be aware of other hikers. I placed this one in a less frequently used part of the trail, but beware of muggles coming along the trail. The Park Rangers know of this cache and have approved of it giving it Permit #PT-42-06. The Ranger only asks that we, as geocachers, respect the trails and try to avoid creating "social" trails whenever possible. As always please re-hide exactly as you found it (please be sure it can not be seen by casual viewers along the Trail)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is parking at each of the Base Trails Trailheads. The East Pinnacle parking is the least used and closest, but the West Pinnacle parking has Facilities like Bathrooms, a Playground, and Picnic tables. Both have water fountains.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;center&gt;****** Congratulations Old River Runner -- Verified FTF 10-09-06 ******&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;a href="http://ArkGeocaching.org"&gt;&lt;font face="Verdana" size="2"&gt;&lt;img src="http://ArkGeocaching.org/images/CacheBanner_full_ani.gif" alt="ArkGeocaching.org" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364249127"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T15:48:07</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="637986">Wollaston</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Woohoo, another CAA ticked off the list. There was obviously a heavy downpour over the hill today as the water is pouring down the trails. Day 19 visiting from Downunder 🇦🇺, outnabout on a little hunting adventure after another awesome GeoWoodstock. It’s always a great day for caching. 😎
TFTC Gener_Lee

Swapped a Pathtag.

If you’ve been to a GeoWoodstock you’re already checking out next years event. If not, check out GCBNWDV GeoWoodstock 2027 in Baton Rouge, Louisiana. May 29, 2027 and log a will attend to do your bit in achieving GIGA status. It’s a bucket list event that never disappoints.

Log my GW Ambassador trackable:  AM1889.   🙂</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363607354"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T20:33:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="54718035">Trailblazerbuster73</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Submitted via Garmin Live Geocaching</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363881579"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="48318008">dobiest</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Quick find here on my first journey through Arkansas. This was a really nice hike and a great spot for a cache. TFTC SL </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363875978"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2464712">Troopbiz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Cache Across America - Arkansas**
**Find #22793**
**Cache Across America #35**

**About This Cache**
Soooo... interesting story about this one.

When planning my trip to GeoWoodstock XXII, I was looking at the surrounding states and thinking I could snag a significant amount of target caches while in the deep south, including this one. Without much research, I added it to the list, only to realize the night before that it was likely missing. CRAP! We can't come all this way and NOT get a smiley on this cache. After all, this was my first time in Arkansas, and I don't have any immediate plans on being anywhere close to here again!

So, I exercised my power as a CAA hider and reached out to LorrieBird, who gave me the blessing to replace the cache (along with the code number). DOBIEST and I stopped at a store along our drive to prep a new container - logbook, SWAG, and all the goodies! It's a CAA after all, so we had to do it right.

Got to the parking area earlier than expected, which meant there was plenty of daylight to make the short walk back to GZ. The park was busy today, but understandably so; this is a beautiful area. It wasn't long before the GPS was in single digits, and we spotted the distraught SWAG that others mentioned. Although, a few feet away, we noticed a strange pile of sticks. What's that?! Was the cache actually here this whole time?!

Turns out, Mouse and Jen had the same idea and left a replacement only a few hours ago! WHOA! What are the odds? They did a nice job getting this cache back on the map, so we transferred the SWAG and travel bugs to our slightly larger and more robust container, and replaced as found. Love to see the caching community helping keep important hides like this one alive. It's a great area - although, the rocks across the trail would make for a much better hiding spot if the CO ever got the inkling to move it.

All is well here and ready to be found! Come and get it! TFTC SL

**About My Trip**
Caching from Hutchinson to Little Rock today with DOBIEST after attending GeoWoodstock XXII in Kansas. It’s a long day on the road, but we picked up a lot of great counties, Arkansas’ oldest, Cache Odyssey, and even Cache Across America. All logs are signed “TB” or “Troopbiz”. Thanks, Gener_Lee, for placing and maintaining this cache! TFTC SL</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363174341"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8218630">itwasmymouse</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Nice morning hike! No luck with an immediate search at GZ. I examined photos and guaranteed that I was at the right spot. Found all the sticker swag debris leftover. Dug a little more in the foilage and found more swag. The cache was stolen! 

I gave it a good hard search: 200ft radius. I wonder if the recent forest fire had anything to do with it. 

Cache is now a PBJ at coordinates 15ft from the trail by a medium sized rock. 

I visited with a previous finder so we had the code. The code is recorded on the lids, baggies and logsheets. 

If everyone keeps a geopile on the cache, it will survive longer. 

Geocaching from Sylvania, Ohio. Stamped/signed logs as itwasmymouse or Mouse. 

Caching and spending time with JenOvations, we use our joint stamp on most logs. We have the MOST fun together. 

Thanks for adding to my adventure and helping me with various goals, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="37.418917" lon="-122.06865"><time>2006-08-21T00:00:00</time><name>GCXWRQ</name><desc>Cache Across  America - California by Mystery Ink.  Adopted by rragan</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXWRQ</url><urlname>Cache Across  America - California</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="449742" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across  America - California</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Mystery Ink.  Adopted by rragan</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="78712">rragan</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="29" inc="0">Telephone nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="36" inc="0">Snowmobiles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="11" inc="1">May require wading</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>California</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;table width="78%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="195" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#B6B792"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;California&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://i12.photobucket.com/albums/a240/Sc0oByDo0/Cache%20Across%20America%20Images/ca-flag.gif" width="180" height="140" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Sacramento&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Los Angeles&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 3rd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 1st&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 31st&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Flower:California Poppy&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Tree:California Redwood&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Animal:California Grizzly&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Marine Animal:Gray Whale&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;State Bird:California Quail&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?IID=af4b9c04-eb98-43ba-9803-98e2ed1a32a5&amp;amp;LID=18268102"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/display/af4b9c04-eb98-43ba-9803-98e2ed1a32a5.jpg" width="113" height="75" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?LUID=8271a556-cf70-4fe6-be1d-624d5c7926e1&amp;amp;IID=d09e4b5c-9846-4018-bbfb-e05dc11bd27b"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/d09e4b5c-9846-4018-bbfb-e05dc11bd27b.jpg" width="113" height="75" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?LUID=8271a556-cf70-4fe6-be1d-624d5c7926e1&amp;amp;IID=e2cd4709-341a-40ce-882f-3274a6eb78b5"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/e2cd4709-341a-40ce-882f-3274a6eb78b5.jpg" width="113" height="75" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?IID=be76407e-0321-4d28-9c58-013c12979a02&amp;amp;LID=18301960"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/be76407e-0321-4d28-9c58-013c12979a02.jpg" width="113" height="75" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/log.aspx?LUID=02fb0012-aeb8-49da-b961-4a85415a506e&amp;amp;IID=2074b2ca-47a8-444b-8ac6-94d96c0c9fe5"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/log/8d47737b-2715-43dc-9808-9840764d8837.jpg" width="113" height="75" border="1" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style2"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="435" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#749974"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;&lt;img src="http://i12.photobucket.com/albums/a240/Sc0oByDo0/Cache%20Across%20America%20Images/photo_ames_moffett_aerial.jpg" width="440" height="300" /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
Moffett Field was established in 1931 to house Navy dirigibles intended to support the U.S. Naval Fleet's Pacific Ocean maneuvers. Hangar 1 was built to house the USS Macon. In 1945 the airfield was renamed after Admiral Moffett, who lost his life in the 1933 USS Akron's crash, and the runways were improved to handle modern aircraft.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;By 1950 jet aircraft replaced dirigible operations. Moffett Field became the largest Naval Air Transport base on the West Coast. Most Eastside/Airfield district buildings were constructed in the 1940s to 1960s. Intense jet aircraft operations at Moffett Field ended in 1963, due to noise and air traffic issues. Navy Orion P-3 long-range ocean surveillance aircraft began operations. The Navy transferred the airfield to NASA in 1994, and Moffett Federal Airfield was established as a limited-use federal airfield.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Moffett Field Today&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A lot of wonderful things are planned for Moffett Field in the near future, but even today the field is a very interesting place to visit. It's literally a place where our future meets our past. Historic landmarks, and buildings near them, house people who doing great things; from building pieces of the international space station at NASA, to retaining pieces of the field's history in historic Hangar 1.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;NASA Ames Research Center and Museum&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Ames Research Center currently operates a small museum which highlights the work scientists from Ames have done over the past decades.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Moffett Field Historical Museum&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Open Wednesday through Saturday, 10AM-3PM admission is free&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Moffett Field Historical Society is always working to record and retain information about the field's rich history. One way they do that is by running this museum located within historic Hangar 1. Artifacts, exhibits, and even a gift shop full of unique merchandise welcome visitors who come to visit. A very interesting place, that is often over looked by other local guides.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hangar 1&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hangar 1 has been a Santa Clara Valley landmark since 1933. It still stands today, and is often used for conventions, private parties, and annual air shows. This massive hangar is truly an amazing sight. When looking up at the ceiling from the floor of the hangar, visitors often feel a sense of vertigo. The hangar is so tall and massive, that fog sometimes forms within it. The panels covering it were found to contain asbestos and were removed between 2010 and 2012. Planetary Ventures (a subsididiary of Google) now leases the hangar and plans a full restoration by 2025. Nearby is the California Air and Space Center. They have a lot to do with developing the Mars Rovers.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I chose this location not only because it's a big piece of history for our State but worldwide with the research that goes on. There are also many other things of interest around this area the technology plus Wetlands near this location. Google, Microsoft, the Computer Tech Museum, SGI as well as aerospace firms reside nearby. Silicon Valley is where a lot of the technology boom started. Be sure to spend a few hours here. There are tons of caches near here and a lot of history around this cache. Code is on the Log book and under the lid. This cache is located right along the Stevens creek trail. BTW Watch out for Skunks they chase.. We were chased by one while placing. Be sure to get the numbers off the lid or log book and take a picture if you are going for all 50 states and the grand cache at the end. For all others, just log this as a regular cache.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Since there is a lot of foot traffic along the adjacent Steven's Creek Trail, take care when retrieving and rehiding to preserve the cache&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#9C856F"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of you group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.thegba.net"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.thegba.net/images/gba_rss.gif" alt="Geocachers of the Bay Area" border="0" height="50" width="174" vspace="5" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>On the lower level by the creek

</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1195028550"><groundspeak:date>2023-09-15T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7056979">gerfmeister</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I forgot to log this one from my trip to Cachin' the Bay.  Was a pleasant walk amongst all the Google muggles circulating along the pathways.  The container was in that cluster of downed trees, and it was fun "skating" down the hill a bit, but everything was in good shape.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1188921680"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-17T15:58:47</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="78712">rragan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The end of a long life. This was one of the 2006 original CAA hides. Two brutal winters sent the adjacent creek out of it's banks  and took out all the trees next to the creek. Some of those trees provided cover for the ammo can. It survived but the trees did not. Now it lies among a tangle of downed trunks. There is no viable place to move it to any longer so I found a new home with lots to show off what makes California special. 

Go find it at CAA CA reincarnated. GCABQWB
Code remains the same. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1188024312"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-13T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3983200">TikvaNZ</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">@1425
Returned to take photo and collect the code. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1183979484"><groundspeak:date>2023-07-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="78712">rragan</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It will soon be time for this one to go. It is the original CAA California and has been around since August 2006 and garnered 52 favorites. Sadly, the last two heavy  weather winters have sent high water down Steven's Creek and uprooted  all the trees used for the hiding the cache. It survived but the area is now a piled up tree zone and will be cleared out sometime in the near future (date unknown) by the water district. There are no other viable places to relocate the old one so it will have to go.

The new one is in a more scenic place, Purisima Creek Redwoods and shows off California well, I believe. 

https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCABQWB_cache-across-america-california

I will leave the old temporary container in place up to 8/15 in case some of you have plans built around finding this one. Shortly after that, I will remove the container and archive it. Thanks to all who visited my old friend here but time for new adventures.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1182964202"><groundspeak:date>2023-07-23T07:01:13</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3983200">TikvaNZ</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#20453 @0700
In the US for a month from Australia. This was my first find here. And hope to pick up a few other states while I'm here. Cache soon found, on a very warm morning. (Unfortunately, I forgot to take the required photo, and note the code, so will try and drop by again 14 August. TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.9799" lon="-105.4545"><time>2007-05-02T00:00:00</time><name>GC12D52</name><desc>Cache Across America - Colorado (#2 old) by cameltrekor</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC12D52</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Colorado (#2 old)</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="584633" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Colorado (#2 old)</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>cameltrekor</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="37229">cameltrekor</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Colorado</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache may be hard to find. EPE at placement was +/-20 ft.
