&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/46/Flag_of_Colorado.svg/800px-Flag_of_Colorado.svg.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Denver&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Denver&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 8th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 22nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 38th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"
   target="_blank"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"
   target="_blank"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's
   capital upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; This cache is placed in what
I think is a typical Colorado high country vista. Here you can see
both the old and the new of Colorado. To get to it you have to
navigate a 2WD dirt road and either (a) a short uphill hike or (b)
the available jeep trail (see map below).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache is close to examples of what makes Colorado unique.
The main parking is part of a ghost town (Caribou). There are
silver mines about, both old and new. To the south is Eldora ski
area. And to the north is Indian Peaks Wilderness and Rocky
Mountain National Park. Nearby are the eclectic towns of Nederland
and Ward; and off to the east is the booming Front Range
metropolis.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Spring brings new growth, for both plant and animal; summer
fills the fields with flowers; fall drops the color and
temperature; and in the winter lots of snow, wind and solitude.
Plan your visit wisely.&lt;/p&gt;
This link will provide a &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://instaar.colorado.edu/tundracam/index.php" target=
"_blank"&gt;good idea of the current weather&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache!&lt;br&gt;
 Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocachingcolo.com"
target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/07725843-2df2-4f12-a33a-0b663ad8fda4.jpg"
     alt="Geocaching Colorado"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="26367927"><groundspeak:date>2007-05-03T09:36:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37229">cameltrekor</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This cache is closed and removed. The new CAA-CO cache is GC12D52.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="25858656"><groundspeak:date>2007-04-21T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37229">cameltrekor</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I went by today with a Sherpa (my dog) to check on the cache. There was no snow around it, but it was encased with four inches of ice. I used my pointy thingy (ice axe) to free the cache. No snowshoes were needed. I have pulled the cache since I punctured it during its escape.

I am working on a location that will be more accessible for others and will advise when this is done.
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="24926353"><groundspeak:date>2007-03-31T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="519331">usyoopers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Well, we were warned, but chose to try, anyway. We hail from Michigan's Upper Peninsula, hence "usyoopers", and don't get to this part of the country very often, in fact this is our second trip in 50 years. After perusing the maps and other info for quite some time we wound through the mountain roads from Denver and finally up the dirt roads to the trailhead. There are signs clearly threatening a $1000.00 fine for using motor vehicles off-road in this area, so I would caution anyone concidering using a Jeep as recomended.A mostly clear and sunny day, with some gusty wind, we set off for the 1/2 mile trek across the snow with snow shovel in tow. After a couple hundred yards, the altitude started Mrs. usyoopers asthma going, so she turned back, but I trekked on. Not used to the altitude, I had to stop often to catch my breath, which I thought odd as others concider me superbly fit, having completed many Ironman Triathlons. As I gained altitude (10,000 ft.), the wind gusts began to concern me, I took 2 steps forward and was blown one step back. When I crested the dome, I'm sure the wind was a constant 80 MPH, I took cover till it subsided. Then I started shoveling, and shoveling, and shoveling. Being a concerned wife, I had to promise Mrs. usyoopers I would be back in 1 hour, so after 1/2 hour shoveling I had to bag it and head down.

I think this cache may only be available 2 or three months out of the year, and only available to those of superb physical fitness. While no 'special equipment' is needed (except maybe oxygen, available at most welding supply stores) I don't think this cache is do-able for the average geocacher on a good day.

Being a "Cache Across America" cache, one would think the cache would be available to any geochacher at any time. The task of getting one cache in each state is formidable enough without the additional challenge of mountaineering.

PS: the highest point in Michigan is just over 2000 feet, an iron ore tailing pile at a mine site.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="23947381"><groundspeak:date>2007-03-04T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37229">cameltrekor</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I went by today to check on the availability of this cache. It is currently covered with up to 2 feet of snow and ice. I will leave it marked as unavailable, but if anyone wants to dig snow it is there.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="22599485"><groundspeak:date>2007-01-17T07:52:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37229">cameltrekor</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Since it is getting into the real winter, I am disabling this until I can get up and check the winter conditions.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.82185" lon="-72.479117"><time>2006-09-12T00:00:00</time><name>GCY9H4</name><desc>Cache Across America – Connecticut by Heckle and Daddy's girl</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCY9H4</url><urlname>Cache Across America – Connecticut</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Multi-cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="461999" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America – Connecticut</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Heckle and Daddy's girl</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="599175">heckle</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Multi-cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Connecticut</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Connecticut&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/Flag_of_Connecticut.svg/694px-Flag_of_Connecticut.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Hartford&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Bridgeport&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 48th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 29th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 5th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; For 120 years, a railroad had operated through Vernon. Once a bustling railroad corridor, the railroad has long since left Vernon. The last freight train passed through town in 1970. The rails were removed in the mid 1970's, but the roadbed remains. Today, the old railroad route is part of Vernon's Rails to Trails linear park.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Vernon Depot passenger station was located on the narrow strip of land that is bordered by Church Street, Phoenix Street, Birch Road and Washington Street. Today, nature has reclaimed the area, but there are still reminders of the past. Near the recently cleared picnic area across from the Church Street parking area, the turntable pit that once turned around the locomotives making the trip to Rockville and back remains. A short distance from there, the footings for the water tank poke out of the ground. There is a visitors shelter, built as a Boy Scouting project, on the footprint of the old passenger station. Its unique roof built to resemble that of the original building. Near there, a short telegraph pole sticks out of the ground about 7 feet. It had at one time supported two wood boxes that I'm told were for communication devices. The holes for the fasteners are still there.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There are some interesting spots here. You can still see the foundation of where the water tower must have been at. With the circular area ringed with stones. It is used alot so the muggle factor may be high so stealth may be needed although the cache final is hidden out of sight. Please do not bushwack to or away from the final as we don't want to create a giveaway path for the muggles to follow.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Cache Details:&lt;/strong&gt; This was originally a short multi but, due to problems with the first part not being put back correctly (causing it to be muggled), if is no longer a multi.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Please do not go directly (straight line) from Parking area to the cache.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364818172"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T09:25:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6478470">Sweet Tides Crew</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 6 of the MA road trip - Today we are playing golf at Gillette Ridge. We decided to find a few caches before our round.

There were a million muggles on the main trail so we snuck up on it from behind. There were so many possible hiding places but we found it pretty quickly.

TFTC 
Sweet Tides Crew</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362194132"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T14:53:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2346848">pommesdeterre8</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Came out this way for some nesgawet mileage and saw id missed a few on the HRLT so aligned my plans accordingly. 

The trail was peaceful, the foliage a kaleidoscope of green and yellow, where dappled sunlight danced through the canopy and cool, merciful breezes drifted through the trees.

Avenging this DNF was 10 years in the waiting. 

Circa2016
😅😂
*Saw a suspicious pile of rocks and got excited
bent over and saw a container and got excited
and
opened up the container
then saw it was
a stoooopid letter box
thanks for nuttin*😂😅

Older and (hopefully a little) wiser... let the geosense guide rather than the phone compass and soon had this cache in hand.

Thanks for the memory.
TFTS
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359801309"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T14:49:51</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="19998847">LindaWaWa</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC found with My Awesome Husband Joey and my Amazing son Benjamin and Wonderful girlfriend Marie while on a trip to watch Jacob Graduate from UCONN </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1361015017"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18168412">benfro2003</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found with mom, dad, and girlfriend. Nice easy find. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360349246"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="18162746">jofro62</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Traveled from Newport News, VA, to visit family in Connecticut and did a quick cache check to see if anything notable nearby would pop up. Happily surprised to see a this CAA hide less than half a mile from their home! Zipped over for the quick find. All in good shape at GZ. TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="38.48685" lon="-75.077283"><time>2006-10-31T00:00:00</time><name>GCYZCB</name><desc>Cache Across America - Delaware by DiS02</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCYZCB</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Delaware</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="482032" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Delaware</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>DiS02</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="363370">DiS02</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="22" inc="1">Hunting area</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Delaware</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
