    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; In 1976, an event occured in
Teton Idaho that has made a mark in &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.idahohistory.net/"&gt;Idaho History&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a rel="nofollow"
href="http://www.usbr.gov/pn/about/Teton.html"&gt;The Failure of Teton
Dam&lt;/a&gt;. The failure of Teton Dam resulted in the loss of 11 lives
and millions of dollars in property damage, forcing thousands to
flee their homes.&lt;br&gt;
&lt;br&gt;
You can see it all from the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/2977dc50-c1a7-4645-a1ae-639ffd24c85f.jpg"&gt;
lookout point&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While passing by Rexburg to get to Teton, stop in and visit the
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.rexcc.com/thingstodo/attractions/tetonflood.html"&gt;Teton
Flood Museum&lt;/a&gt;, which is housed in the basement of a historic
Tabernacle.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of you group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Follow the fence towards 'R' mountain (West of Lookout)</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="567238372"><groundspeak:date>2016-01-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15177653">ExpLaur</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Previously logged as GaxnLa and critln58 (now Gax2884).</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="360604545"><groundspeak:date>2013-10-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Great news, Cache Across America watchers!  The brand new CAA Idaho is now published and ready to go!  The new cache is GC4QRVD.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="349143306"><groundspeak:date>2013-09-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Many thanks to the reviewer for helping us move on to the future Cache Across America Idaho!

This cache will no longer count as the CAA Idaho find and the three digit code is no longer available.  There is a new CAA Idaho in the works . We do not yet know the new location but will update the bookmarks as soon as this information is available. 

Thank you CAA seekers for your patience... we are looking forward to having this gorgeous state once again represented!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="349033143"><groundspeak:date>2013-09-09T16:39:05</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6200080">Agramone</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Even though there appears to be a cache container here, it is not the proper one, placed by the owner, with the necessary puzzle piece accompanying it so that cachers can get the final cache in the series.  Unfortunately there has been no response from the owner regarding this cache, and sadly I am forced to archive it at this time. If at some point in the near future the cache is determined to still be present or is replaced, please e-mail me via the link on my profile page. If it still meets the current guidelines, we can discuss unarchiving it at that time.

Thank you,

Agramone
Volunteer Geocaching.com reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="346667493"><groundspeak:date>2013-08-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2361499">Messingaround</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We are on a 7 state CAA run this weekend, and this is our 4th.  We'll post the pic as soon as we download the pictures.  We were running a little behind and had to pick this one up at night (10:34 pm), as will be evident from the pic we'll post.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.948817" lon="-88.734833"><time>2006-11-04T00:00:00</time><name>GCZ7A3</name><desc>Cache Across America - Illinois by baloo&amp;bd</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCZ7A3</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Illinois</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="489650" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Illinois</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>baloo&amp;bd</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="112813">baloo&amp;bd</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="36" inc="0">Snowmobiles</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Illinois</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>This cache is right off a paved path. It is listed as a 1.5 terrain
only because it is not considered handicap accessible. There should
be no bushwacking involved.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Illinois&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/Illinois_state_flag.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Springfield&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Chicago&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 25th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 5th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 21st&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We chose to place this in DeKalb Illinois because this area
typifies towns as they have existed for may decades in Illinois&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;font color="#000000" face="Times New Roman"&gt;&lt;span lang=
"EN"&gt;Founded in 1837, DeKalb remained a small community until the
arrival of the&lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://dig.lib.niu.edu/dekalb/hist-rail.html"&gt;Chicago and
Northwestern Railroad&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;span style=
"font-family: Times New Roman;" lang="EN"&gt;&lt;font color=
"#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;in 1853. DeKalb received its charter in
1856. DeKalb's central location brought easier shipping of crops
and access to larger markets. Agriculture was the primary economic
activity until the 1873-4 when farmer&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman" lang=
      "EN"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow"
      href="http://www.gliddenhomestead.org/"&gt;Joseph Glidden&lt;/a&gt;
      developed&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=
      "font-family: Times New Roman; font-size: 12pt" lang=
      "EN"&gt;&lt;a tip="Barbed wire" style=
      "color: blue; text-decoration: underline;" href=
      "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barbed_wire"&gt;&lt;span style=
      "color: windowtext; text-decoration: none"&gt;barbed
      wire&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt; &lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
      lang="EN"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;and began
      commercial mass production of his new invention. Glidden sold
      half of his interest to hardware
      merchant&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=
      "font-family: Times New Roman;" lang="EN"&gt;&lt;font color=
      "#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
      "http://www.ellwoodhouse.org/barb_wire/"&gt;Issac L. Ellwood&lt;/a&gt;
      and together the two formed the Barb Fence Company. Two
      months after Glidden filed his application for a patent,
      lumber salesman&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=
      "font-family: Times New Roman;" lang="EN"&gt;&lt;font color=
      "#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
      "http://dig.lib.niu.edu/dekalb/hist-haishhome.html"&gt;Jacob
      Haish&lt;/a&gt; also applied for a patent and on June 25, 1874, ran
      interference papers against Glidden's patent. After 18 years
      of legal wrangling, Glidden's patent was declared the
      "Winner". The industry gave DeKalb a place in history and the
      nickname "Barb City". In 1865&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;a tip=
      "H. B. Gurler" style=
      "color: blue; text-decoration: underline;" href=
      "http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=H._B._Gurler&amp;amp;action=edit"&gt;
&lt;span style="color: windowtext; text-decoration: none"&gt;H. B.
Gurler&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman;"
      lang="EN"&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN"&gt;moved to
      DeKalb, and later attempted to create high-grade milk. Gurler
      began shipping his "&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;a tip=
      "http://www.bios.niu.edu/gurler/puremilk.htm" style=
      "color: blue; text-decoration: underline;" href=
      "http://www.bios.niu.edu/gurler/puremilk.htm"&gt;&lt;span style=
      "color: windowtext; text-decoration: none"&gt;Pure
      Milk&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;font color="#000000"&gt;&lt;span lang="EN" style=
      "font-family: Times New Roman"&gt;" to Chicago in 1895. The
      founding of &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
      "http://dig.lib.niu.edu/dekalb/hist-normal.html"&gt;Northern
      Illinois State Normal School&lt;/a&gt; in 1895 added education to
      DeKalb's landscape. Agriculture again came to the forefront
      with the creation of the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
      "http://www.dekalbfarmbureau.org/"&gt;DeKalb County Farm
      Bureau&lt;/a&gt; in 1912, the first organization of its kind. In
      the 1930s the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
      "http://www3.niu.edu/historicalbuildings/dekalb_summary.htm"&gt;DeKalb
      AgResearch Corporation&lt;/a&gt; marketed its first hybrid seed
      corn.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="font-family: Times New Roman" lang="en-us"&gt;To the
southwest of this cache you will find the &lt;a rel="nofollow"
   href="http://www.ellwoodhouse.org/barb_wire/"&gt;Elwood Estate
   Museum&lt;/a&gt; and to the northeast the town of &lt;a rel="nofollow"
   href="http://www.cityofsycamore.com/"&gt;Sycamore, Illinois&lt;/a&gt;,
   which has a rich history in it's own right.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="843597579"><groundspeak:date>2019-04-21T20:17:23</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="112813">baloo&amp;bd</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">After repeated attempts to get a replacement code for the container, the people responsible for the series have decided to have another cache placed for Illinois.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="843130393"><groundspeak:date>2019-04-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8617946">Bass Brigade</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In the area from 2 hours SE to attend an event at Sycamore Community Park. After a fun day of meeting new friends we picked up 4 caches that caught our attention on the round about way back to I-88. GPS bounces as we approached GZ but only 1 beacon stood out like a sore thumb! TFTC! SL in red ink as Bass Brigade.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="842894035"><groundspeak:date>2019-04-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello Cache Across America watchers and players. The CAA series would like to announce that a new CAA for the state of Illinois has now been published and going forward will be the official cache for Illinois in the series.  Publishing a new CAA cache is always a very bittersweet thing for the series, as we always try to keep the older ones up and running for as long as humanly possible. This old classic had a wonderful run of 12 years (!), but time had marched on and the long run of the CAA IL GCZ7A3 had come to an end. We are ever grateful for the hard working ownership of baloo&amp;bd for many years, as owning a CAA cache is a lot of work and can sometimes be a thankless job. I will always have fond memories of my old favorite CAA IL as it once had one of the best hiding places ever! I have posted my own photo of the sadly long gone location with this log. The master list of CAA caches has been updated to reflect the change.  Cachers can find the complete list of CAA caches, both past and present here:

https://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?code=BM21GBP</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="840412160"><groundspeak:date>2019-04-11T16:35:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="21643333">junior41</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Got’em

Cool little hike to find this cache

Signed log
Left mini-domino (3/0) inside cache

TMNT Raphael is my Geocache partner and when found cache there is a TMNT G1 sticker within the cache already ....awesome!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="839492865"><groundspeak:date>2019-04-07T15:38:48</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2887256">zatnkat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We were lucky to get a short break in the rain today as we made our way to the cache. This is our 42nd find in the Cache Across America (CAA) series. We will attempt to get 3 more on this short road trip from Florida — Iowa, Minnesota and Wisconsin. 

As noted by previous cachers, the CAA code is missing from this geocache. We will try to get it from the CO or the series coordinator. 

Best, ZATnKAT</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="37.46705" lon="-88.160833"><time>2006-10-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCYRGY</name><desc>Cache Across America - Illinois by Beffums &amp; Japtkd</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCYRGY</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Illinois</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="476408" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Illinois</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Beffums &amp; Japtkd</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="410053">Beffums</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Illinois</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Illinois&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/30/Illinois_state_flag.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Springfield&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Chicago&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 25th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 5th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 21st&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to
   &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Welcome to Illinois - the
Land of Lincoln! If you follow the Lincoln Heritage Trail to its
end, you will find yourself in picturesque Cave-in-Rock Illinois,
where you will be able to begin your search for the cache. The
cache is located in Cave-in-Rock state park along a less-traveled
footpath at the base of the cliffs/bluffs. There are stone stairs
from the parking and picnicking areas down to the level of the main
cave and the footpath to the cache. While you are walking along the
footpath, enjoy the beautiful views along the Ohio - but please
take care to also watch your step! The footpath wanders over many
stones that have fallen from the cliff face; a cacher who does not
watch their feet will likely trip and fall. Parents of young
children should be especially careful while walking near the edges
at the top of the bluffs/cliffs.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cache details: The cache is a large lock-n-lock style container
(5"x5"x10") filled with a variety of swag. According to Illinois
DNR policies, it is the responsibility of visitors to orient
themselves with policies and rules pertaining to this Department
managed site. Please do NOT place any of the following into the
cache: Food items and/or inappropriate, offensive, or hazardous
materials. Given the possibility of muggles, please rehide the
cache as found.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cave-in-Rock was first discovered by a French explorer in 1729.
Following the Revolutionary War, the large cavern formed the ideal
hideaway for outlaws, bandits and river pirates who preyed on the
travelers on the Ohio River. The cave served as the background in
the movie “How The West Was Won” in a scene portraying ruthless
bandits using the cave to lure unsuspecting travelers to an
untimely end. Illinois historian John W. Allen had this to say
about the park: “Today only the natural beauty of the historic spot
remains, clothed in mystery. In the hollow silence of the cave that
echoes the peaceful cooing of doves, a visitor can let a vivid
imagination run riot. But he can dream little that will be beyond
what actually happened.”&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Cave in Rock is a 200+ acre state park along the banks of the
Ohio River in southeastern Illinois. It features two hiking trails,
tent and RV camping facilities, lodges and cabins, a small
playground for children, and a restaurant. The Ohio River provides
access for boating and fishing, and the park has a marina for
larger craft. It also has picnic areas and shelters for larger
groups. Admission is free to the park itself (but there are fees
for camping, lodging, and the like). It is located in Cave in Rock,
IL, a town with a population of roughly 300, located at the
terminus of IL-1, the southern branch of the "Lincoln Heritage
Trail." Cave-in-Rock has small boutiques and restaurants, and a
marker noting where Lewis and Clark passed through on their journey
west. The Cave-in-Rock ferry shuttles cars and pedestrians across
the Ohio River to Kentucky and back.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;When most Americans think of Illinois, we think of Chicago and
Abe Lincoln. Many cachers might also think of the BOB series of
caches or the APE cache near the Chicago area. One goal with this
cache was to encourage cachers to explore other areas of the state
- particularly some of the scenic and beautiful areas in the
southern portions of the state. Come, find this cache, and make
sure to walk into the cave itself, to see what has amazed explorers
for centuries. While you are in southeastern Illinois, we encourage
you to explore the neighboring Shawnee National Forest (and its
caches!) including the awe-inspiring "Garden of the Gods". You can
head southwest from here, and enter "Little Egypt" Illinois, where
the original settlers would travel to find grains and other foods
in the bounty provided along the banks of the Ohio and the
Mississippi. Or, take one of the ferries across the Ohio River and
explore the neighboring sections of Kentucky.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache has been placed with permission by the park manager
(Mike) at Cave-in-Rock State Park. The park closes at 10 pm (unless
you are camping or lodging overnight). Please do not attempt this
cache after hours, and be careful during hours if it is dark out.
Please be particularly careful if the river is nearing flood stages
as you will be walking within 25 feet of the river most of the way.
If you have any questions about this cache, please feel free to
contact me or the park (618-289-4325). If you are traveling a long
distance to this cache, please do not hesitate to contact me before
coming - I will happily check on the cache before your trip to
ensure you have something to find!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>near the back of the large crevice, under rocks</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="20233661"><groundspeak:date>2006-10-26T05:54:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="410053">Beffums</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A new cache in the series will soon be appearing in Northern Illinois, away from the juvenile antics of a single unlikeable individual in the southern portion of the state.  It's a shame that one idiot is ruining things for everyone else.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="20203654"><groundspeak:date>2006-10-24T15:38:25</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="410053">Beffums</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Will likely be archiving soon.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="19872100"><groundspeak:date>2006-10-14T00:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="404557">japtkd</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Bug drop.  Zephyr just wants to see the world.  Not end up in someone's coin album.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="19870181"><groundspeak:date>2006-10-13T22:15:20</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="309660">Reviewer Jones</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Published</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.2416" lon="-85.81765"><time>2009-01-27T00:00:00</time><name>GC1M5BE</name><desc>Cache Across America - Indiana by Kosciusko County Visitors Center</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1M5BE</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Indiana</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1113381" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Indiana</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Kosciusko County Visitors Center</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1893214">LLLGL</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Other</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="1">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Indiana</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Indiana&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Flag_of_Indiana.svg/744px-Flag_of_Indiana.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Indianapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Indianapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 38th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 15th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 19th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;This cache is located at the Kosciusko County Visitors Center and, according to geocachers who have already visited, is in one of the coolest geocache containers ever! While you are caching, take a few minutes to stop in the Visitor Center and check out information on the area and on the entire state of Indiana. The Visitor Center is a great resource for visitors to Indiana. Whether it is your first visit or you have been to Indiana countless times, there are always new things to learn about in our great state.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kosciusko County is such a beautiful area. It is a mostly rural county with only one community large enough to be classified a city. Fields of corn and soybeans greet the visitor from just about every angle. But don't be fooled ... there's way more than corn in Indiana (and in Kosciusko County!).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kosciusko County is home to over 100 lakes including Indiana's largest nature lake, Lake Wawasee, and Indiana's deepest lake, Tippecanoe Lake.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Kosciusko County is also home to the world headquarters of five large orthopedic manufacturers, earning it the title Orthopedic Capital of the World. Orthopedic implements made right here in Kosciusko County are sent around the world; Olympic Gymnast Mary Lou Retton and the late Pope John Paul II both received implements manufactured right here in Kosciusko County. Little Crow Foods, makers of CoCo Wheats cereal and Fryin Magic, started operations in 1903 in Kosciusko County and have been making their products here even since. Louis Dreyfus, in Claypool, is the world's largest bio-diesel fuel plant.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So take some time to slow down in Kosciusko County. Our small town values and rural charm will bring you back again and again.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache was formerly called the Travel Bug Visitors Center. It's still a great place to drop Travel Bugs!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="607636064"><groundspeak:date>2016-06-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cache Across America players:

The Cache Across America - Indiana cache has now been republished as GC6HCCW.

It is in the same location as the old one and the Kosciusko County Visitors Center will remain the caretakers of this cache for as long as they want to keep it on their property.

A special 'Thank You' to reviewer Hoosier Reviewer who was instrumental in keeping the CAA IN cache in this location and available to all!

Cache on.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="607503589"><groundspeak:date>2016-06-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dear Cache Across America watchers and players.

The Cache Across America Indiana cache is in the process of being replaced with an active owner and we hope to have the new page published soon.

The CAA IN cache will remain at the Visitors Center location as it always has been.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="607464249"><groundspeak:date>2016-06-06T18:55:40</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6389491">Hoosier_Reviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Since there has been no response to my previous note, I am archiving the cache.


Hoosier Reviewer
Geocaching.com Volunteer Cache Reviewer

**NOTE: do not select reply in your e-mail program if you wish to respond to this message from the geocaching.com mail bot. Go to your cache page and e-mail Hoosier Reviewer from the log there or email me directly at hoosierreviewer@gmail.com, referencing the cache URL, or waypoint number.**</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="605322955"><groundspeak:date>2016-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5377235">AngelusCowl</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this one this evening. Made this my find for this county- love this series, can't wait to make more headway on it. Had to dodge some sprinklers while making the find, nice setup. Collected info for the final and took a photo, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="603306207"><groundspeak:date>2016-05-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2948236">FLtravelers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day two of a three day caching trip out of Asheville, NC with PMO. Our primary goal is to finish finding a cache in all of Indiana's counties. In the process, we're targeting earthcaches, virtuals, challenges, and whatever else interesting comes our way. This is certainly one of those. Great cache. TFTC.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.500367" lon="-86.3706"><time>2006-07-08T00:00:00</time><name>GCX1D5</name><desc>Cache Across America – Indiana by sept1c_tank and Flutterbutter</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX1D5</url><urlname>Cache Across America – Indiana</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="424397" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America – Indiana</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>sept1c_tank and Flutterbutter</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="119047">sept1c_tank</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="0">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Indiana</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;p&gt;This cache is near State Road 37, in a peaceful place that is
sinfully, almost literally, a drive-up cache. It is located on
public property completely surrounded by private farmland.
&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="FF0000"&gt;Do not go on private
property.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is no hiking involved. The cache is a lock 'n lock. You
will not feel uncomfortable at this spot because it is a dead end
road with ample area to turn around or park and it is quite removed
from the nearest farm house.&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
 
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Indiana&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ac/Flag_of_Indiana.svg/744px-Flag_of_Indiana.svg.png"
     width="187" height="135" /&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Indianapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Indianapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 38th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 15th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 19th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series
&lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/148cde39-6142-4061-915f-761d14bd0b37.jpg"
     width="187" height="141" /&gt; 
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;
&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to
&lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Contrary to popular belief,&lt;/b&gt; Indiana has more than just
corn and bean fields. The chosen location of this cache
demonstrates some of the rich history and geological wonders of the
19th state. If you study a topographical map of the region, you may
observe that almost everything north of the cache is flat (all the
way to Lake Michigan) and that everything south of the cache (to
the Ohio river) is hilly.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;According to the Indiana Geological Survey: The 30-mile section
of State Road 37 from Waverly to Bloomington crosses several
geologic terrains that formed under widely varying climate
conditions and by glacial and coastal processes that are separated
by 300 million years of time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;The large, nearby ridge&lt;/b&gt; that you can see just southwest
of the cache is the remnant of a large outwash fan deposited by an
ice sheet of Illinoian age, around 300,000 years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For several miles to the north of the cache, the highway
traverses rolling to hummocky topography that flanks the flat
valley of the White River just to the west. This topography
reflects the most recent ice sheet to invade this area, during the
Wisconsin age, some 21,000 years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cuts along the highway about 25 miles south of the cache
near Bloomington reveal limestone and siltstone that accumulated in
Indiana about 340 million years ago. At this time, Indiana was
about 10 to 15 degrees south of the equator in the equatorial
tropics. The siltstones are part of a large delta that spread
sediment westward into a shallow sea from rivers in the east and
northeast part of the state.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;About two miles down river from the cache is the site of Scotts
Ferry (1820-1840). John Scott also ran one of Indiana’s earliest
horse racing tracks near the ferry crossing at the same time.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;Five miles north of the cache&lt;/b&gt; is the birthplace of the
Indiana state flag. Designed by Mooresville, artist Paul Hadley,
the outer circle of stars represents the original thirteen
colonies. The inner circle of stars represents the next five states
admitted to the union and the largest star represents Indiana.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So you see, even though when you find this cache you are out
standing in a field, you are in the midst of a timeline of history,
on a ride through time from the age of dinosaurs to the present.
There are dozens of caches scattered about the nearby landscapes;
only 10 miles south of this cache, in Morgan Monroe State forest,
you can search for some excellent caches on the “rugged side” of
the state.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;i&gt;The original contents of the cache include: two 2006 Indy 500
pins, three Flutterbutter butterfly items, two packaged vintage
Indiana key chains, a flashlight, three geo buttons by bumble
buttons, a package of four AA batteries, the historical fiction
novel Follow the River, by James Alexander Thom, a Hoosier resident
of the Bloomington area, a travel bug, a geocoin and a logbook with
writing utensils.&lt;/i&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="472097901"><groundspeak:date>2013-09-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7994938">1st_mate</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Late log entry. Made this find with captphil a while back when I was logging in under his username. He often referred to me as Mrs. Captphil or 1st mate. Now that I have my own account I would like to claim this as a find. We were traveling to Ft. Sill for our son's graduation from the Captains Career Course. I had recently had surgery for a torn rotator cuff (yep, my only caching injury) and really enjoyed this trip.  TFTFun!! TFTC!!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="83731264"><groundspeak:date>2009-09-08T17:58:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1069637">Reviewer Hilts</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Since I haven't heard from the owner I'm archiving the cache. If the owner wishes to reactivate this cache, please e-mail me at [red]hilts@geocachingadmin.com[/red] and I'll un-archive it as soon as I can.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="81924571"><groundspeak:date>2009-08-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1069637">Reviewer Hilts</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The "temporarily disabled" feature should not be used for extended periods of time. Please either make repairs on this cache or archive it within the next 14 days.

I will check back on September 7th, if the cache has not been repaired or replaced I will be forced to archive it.

[red]Please post a note to the cache page if there are any other issues here.[/red]
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="73468995"><groundspeak:date>2009-06-07T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5602">mcrt</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Well I found it as well as I could with the current state of things. After no response from the CO I contacted Blue Power Ranger to check with what I should do. I figured no matter what I had to stop and sign whatever was there and post a picture. Dropped a Kenyan Shilling into the film canister.

Very cool location. People talk about the flat northern part of the state and the hilly southern part. This really puts it into view. TFTH.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="73584480"><groundspeak:date>2009-06-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2151695">Starck Reality</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Was traveling from Nashville to the Quad Cities with Architrave and was thrilled to be able to go just a little out of the way to get this one.  Started for the replacement cache, but Architrave said he'd go after it since it was in poison ivy.  I'm still dealing with the poison ivy I got from my GeoWoodstock VII caching, so I gladly let him!  

SL.  Thanks to RogFel for replacing this one!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="43.41475" lon="-93.208733"><time>2006-07-22T00:00:00</time><name>GCX9GR</name><desc>Cache Across America - Iowa by The Northwood Goonies</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX9GR</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Iowa</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="432197" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Iowa</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>The Northwood Goonies</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="119736">The Northwood Goonies</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Iowa</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;b&gt;Cache Across America - Iowa&lt;/b&gt;
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Welcome to Iowa, the "Hawkeye" State. Iowa is a land of agriculture... from dairy, beef, and pork to corn and soybeans. Major universities in Iowa include the University of Iowa (Hawkeyes), the University of Northern Iowa (Panthers), and Iowa State University (Cyclones). Movies that were filmed in Iowa include "The Field of Dreams" and "Twister". Hunting is very popular in the state whether you are after the great Whitetail deer, or the Ringnecked Pheasant. This cache will take you through some agricultural areas and small-town Iowa. This cache was placed with permission from the Worth County Conservation Board. CITO must be practiced at all times, and hunting is allowed in all Worth County Conservation Areas.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
To learn more about geocaching in Iowa visit...&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;a href="http://www.iowageocachers.org"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.iowageocachers.org/a_Current_IGO_Banner_1.gif" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Peanut butter jar</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363759716"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T13:20:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="9891300">TheDriver2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC. Found with my son, Paulgracie on our road trip to Wisconsin dells. Cache in good shape.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363645047"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="598646">tdb1977</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On a 2 week trip with my wife to visit close to 20 National Park sites, I was in Iowa today to visit Effigy Mounds.  Before hoping on 35 and heading north towards Minneapolis for the night, we headed for this CAA cache.  Pulled into the park and I made my way up the hill to ground zero.  It didn't take me long to come up with the find here and my 28th CAA cache!  I recorded the number, dropped off a travel bug and placed everything back where it was found.  I also took my selfie here as proof that I actually found the cache.  All is well here.  Thanks for the cache.  Took nothing, left nothing.  Signed the log and placed back where I found it.

TDB1977</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362382623"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T18:26:43</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="42375063">GeoKelterFam</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found it! Took the non T 1.5 path apparently.  Quick one on our way to GWXXII. TFTC 1,3

Cache Across America #3 </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362165536"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-19T11:46:17</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="14566146">CheekyBrit</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This is going to be super helpful on the challenge passport for GCBF8TE. Thats a massive event coming up in Pocatello Idaho, August 22nd. A quick dip onto Kuennen's quarry and I stumbled upon this chap. One more state down and before you know it, I'll HAVE to go to Hawaii.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1351986374"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4217911">foxystevie2</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I spent a good portion of Friday running around and finding Cache Odyssey caches and Cache Across America caches that I felt like I would be silly if I didnt make a stop for this one here today, so off I headed. This was the farthest north I traveled today. I believe I made this one harder than I needed to. This trip, my compass on my phone kept pointing me in the wrong direction. Made me miss my old Garmin. So I made a rugged climb in my gym shoes because I kept forgetting to wear my hiking boots. Thankfully, the ground was still cold and solid. I made the quick find and dashed off to my next stop. Tftc!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.224733" lon="-96.619467"><time>2006-07-15T00:00:00</time><name>GCX5HG</name><desc>Cache Across America -- Kansas by k_statealan</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX5HG</url><urlname>Cache Across America -- Kansas</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="428376" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America -- Kansas</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>k_statealan</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2772045">Semmels123</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="0">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="33" inc="0">Motorcycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="34" inc="0">Quads</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Kansas</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Cache is an ammocan accessible after less than a quarter-mile walk from either of two parking areas. The shorter one will require a little more exertion. There will be about 100' of walking down a hill through waist-high brush. Watch for a few loose rocks and some thorns. Don't access from the highway.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Kansas&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/da/Flag_of_Kansas.svg/750px-Flag_of_Kansas.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Topeka&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Wichita&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 15th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 32nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 34th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; –Welcome to the Flint Hills! The Flint Hills, historically known as Bluestem Pastures, are a band of hills in eastern Kansas, extending from Marshall County in the north, to Cowley and Chautauqua counties in the south. They were named by explorer Zebulon Pike in 1806 for the cobbles of flint-like chert that glinted through the tall prairie grasses. Sparsely populated, the Flint Hills contain most of the remaining tallgrass prairie in North America and has some of the largest cattle ranches in Kansas. The Flint Hills were created approximately 250 million years ago during the Permian Period. During this time much of the Midwest, including Kansas, was covered with shallow seas. As a result, much of the Flint Hills are composed of limestone and shale with plentiful fossils of prehistoric sea creatures. The most notable layer of chert-bearing limestone is the Florence Limestone Member. It is approximately 45 feet thick; numerous roadcuts of the Florence Member are prominent along Interstate 70 in Riley County. Many of the honey-colored limestones have been used for building blocks. The non-chert-bearing limetones are best for this, since the chert is extremely hard to cut, but yet it can fracture quite easily. Beginning in the mid-1800s homesteaders displaced the American Indians and vast herds of grazing buffalo with large cattle ranches. The largest city in the Flint Hills is Manhattan, KS. From the cache site you will be looking down on Manhattan, home of Kansas State University, from one of the highest points in the area. Among the notable sites to see are: *Tuttle Creek Dam and Reservoir to the northeast—one of the largest bodies of water in the state controls flooding of the Blue River Valley and beyond. *Colbert Hills Golf Course to the southwest—A world-class golf course designed by PGA professional and KSU alumnus Jim Colbert. *KS hill to the southeast—One of the other high points around Manhattan and the home of another (more difficult) cache than this one. *Bill Snyder Family Stadium and Bramlage Coliseum to the southeast—Home of the Kansas State (or K-State to the locals) University Wildcat football and basketball teams. The large white building with the Powercat logo is the indoor practice facility for KSU athletics.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under the thorny tree</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364242141"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2787564">driseman</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Gooding off with I and Tizzy.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363739462"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-26T11:31:55</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="4208218">raven45</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Foundvthe narrow well beaten path that took us directly to gz. Nice view from up here.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363590033"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T14:30:35</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1670110">Paddling Pirates</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In the area for GeoWoodstock XXII. Had a great time at all the official events and now doing some stuff on our own. 

A warm day, but a nice view. 

This is one of our bucket list items today. Thanks for placing and maintaining this geocache.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363565237"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T13:11:56</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="637986">Wollaston</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Beautiful day made even better by ticking off another CAA cache. Day 15 visiting from Downunder 🇦🇺, outnabout on a little hunting adventure after another awesome GeoWoodstock. It’s always a great day for caching. 😎
TFTC Semmels123

If you’ve been to a GeoWoodstock you’re already checking out next years event. If not, check out GCBNWDV GeoWoodstock 2027 in Baton Rouge, Louisiana. May 29, 2027 and log a will attend to do your bit in achieving GIGA status. It’s a bucket list event that never disappoints.

Log my GW Ambassador trackable:  AM1889.   🙂</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364267701"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1137940">NextStep_</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Coming home from GeoWoodstock with Nurse Nanna.  We made a detour on the way home to the Tanganika WIldlife park, as she had won tickets in the GeoWoodstock raffle and couldn't wait to see Mars the pygmy hippo.  We had to move quickly to get home after spending half the day there, but did have this cache on our must do list.  It was a nice hike up to the top and we found the cache - harder on the way in, a bit easier on the way out.  With so much traffic, we would have thought there would be more of a geotrail.  Recorded the code and admired the view.  Thanks for the cache!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="37.005083" lon="-86.3759"><time>2006-08-24T00:00:00</time><name>GCXY7V</name><desc>Cache Across America – Kentucky by SG-MIN</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXY7V</url><urlname>Cache Across America – Kentucky</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="451140" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America – Kentucky</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>SG-MIN</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="400543">belltroy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="0">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Kentucky</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Ammo Can hidden as a part of the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
   "http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
Cache Across America Series&lt;/a&gt;. Please replace the cache exactly
where you found it. Since this is connected to a larger series, I
want everyone to be able to find it. I have included my cell number
in the hint as a lifeline for those of you from out of town.</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;table width="77%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="4"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Kentucky&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/69/Kentucky_state_flag.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Frankfort&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Louisville&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 37th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 25th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 15th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America
Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a
caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in
each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue
that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; If you are
attempting to complete the entire &lt;i&gt;Cache Across America&lt;/i&gt;
series, you are sure to put some miles on your vehicle. I am sure
only a few of us are lucky enough to be able to drive the same kind
of cache-car that is honored here.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/199df53a-f02d-4551-8ae4-919a40cd1de4.jpg"
     align="left" border="1" hspace="5"&gt;What a better to place to
     stop on a series dedicated to America than a museum dedicated
     to the American Sports Car!! You will definitely want to
     cruise in to get this cache which is located at the &lt;a rel=
     "nofollow" href="http://www.corvettemuseum.com"&gt;National
     Corvette Museum&lt;/a&gt; in Bowling Green. If at all possible, you
     will want to make time to visit inside the museum as well.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;Since 1953 the Corvette has been America's
Sports Car. The National Corvette Museum was established as a
501(c)3 not-for-profit foundation with a mission of celebrating the
invention of the Corvette and preserving its past, present and
future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;The 68,000 sq. ft. building houses more than 50
Corvette models and one-of-a-kind concept cars spanning the history
of Corvette. Also on hand are thousands of Corvette related photos,
movies and videos, advertisements, scale models and rare
memorabilia. Spotlighted are the people who have made Corvette an
American icon.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/c7e14737-9c0a-4aa8-877b-05d43324c17d.jpg"
     align="right" border="0"&gt;Inside, striking full-scale dioramas
     show classic Corvette models and famous performance Corvette
     models in period settings. You'll also find the historic
     one-millionth Corvette, donated to the museum by Chevrolet.
     You may also want to visit the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
     "http://www.bowlinggreenassemblyplant.com"&gt;Bowling Green
     Assemby Plant&lt;/a&gt;, where the Corvette and Cadillac XLR are
     made.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;This cache is a hidden ammo can that was placed
with permission from the Events Manager at the Corvette Museum. It
is conveniently located right off I-65 and is in an ideal location
for travel bugs. The posted hours of the Museum and this cache are
8am-5pm 7 days a week excluding major holidays. Be sure to bring
your lunch – there are picnic tables nearby.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy
this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache
as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a
photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your
online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo
requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find
with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for
non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds
will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="justify"&gt;If participating in the series, please take note
of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code
in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have
collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final
cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under and up - NE side
two-seven-zero-five-three-five-five-nine-five-six
</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1201413605"><groundspeak:date>2023-05-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="60783">Poke Along</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I have no idea why our log never went through, but I am posting it now. We stop by here to find the cache when no one was around. Who knows what happened to my photo, but we did this one (and all of them) together.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="367598178"><groundspeak:date>2013-11-27T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello Cache Across America watchers! We are happy to report that a new CAA KY has been published and can be found at GC4QDD5.  Thank you for your patience!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="366958613"><groundspeak:date>2013-11-23T19:32:16</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="578183">Bluegrass Reviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Greetings from Geocaching.com,

This cache came up for review while going through all the ones that have been made temporarily unavailable for more than 30 days.

As cache owner, it is your responsibility to either repair or archive any caches that are no longer acceptable for Geocachers to hunt.

Since you have failed to respond to the request for maintenance, we are archiving the cache.

Sincerely,

Bluegrass Reviewer
Geocaching.com Volunteer
Reply to: bluegrassreviewer@gmail.com
Please send the name of the cache and the GC# with your reply</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="366536503"><groundspeak:date>2013-11-21T06:53:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Following up from my post from October.  Still no success in reaching the owner.  Thank you 'belltroy' for your years of service to the geocaching community and to the Cache Across America series.  This cache has been a favorite of many, myself included.  You did a great job with this cache.

I am happy to report that a new Cache Across America - Kentucky is ready to go with a new owner.  The Corvette Museum has been contacted and permission granted to continue hosting the location for the CAA Kentucky cache, and for that we are grateful.  We are very excited about this permission as the Geo Adventure Maze will also be here soon!

Thank you for your patience CAA watchers and players.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="358720868"><groundspeak:date>2013-10-18T05:48:21</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="578183">Bluegrass Reviewer</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello Responsible Cache Owner,

We take all should be archived notices very seriously. What is the status of this cache? Should it be archived? 

As cache owner, it is your responsibility to archive any caches that are no longer acceptable for Geocachers to hunt.

These are the guidelines about cache maintenance:  http://www.geocaching.com/about/guidelines.aspx#cachemaintenance
As a courtesy to your fellow geocachers, the listing has been temporarily disabled until its status is verified. 

If we do not hear from you within 30 days the cache will be archived.

Sincerely,
 
Bluegrass Reviewer
Geocaching.com Volunteer
Reply to: bluegrassreviewer@gmail.com	
Please send the name of the cache and the GC# with your reply</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="31.814433" lon="-93.08445"><time>2006-07-10T00:00:00</time><name>GCX2W4</name><desc>Cache Across America - Louisiana by Team Gryarvold</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX2W4</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Louisiana</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="425791" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Louisiana</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Team Gryarvold</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="638886">Team Gryarvold</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Louisiana</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>We had a major muggle operation and lost the entire first cache, TB's and all. We moved it out of town a ways on the scenic river. It is now a lock and lock well hidden (we hope) with some goodies, although we were out of TB's to replace the others. It has some bushes and vines around it, so may be just a tad difficult for wheelchair by itself, but can get with a buddy.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Louisiana&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e0/Flag_of_Louisiana.svg/800px-Flag_of_Louisiana.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Baton Rouge&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: New Orleans&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 31st&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 22nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 18th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Natchitoches(Nak-i-toosh)is the oldest town in Louisiana and the oldest permanent settlement in the Louisiana Purchase. Established in 1714 by Louis Juchereau de St.Denis, the French settlement had two purposes; to establish trade with the Spanish in Texas and Mexico, and at the same time, to deter Spanish advances into Louisiana. It is believed the French first arrived in the area around 1699. Successful trading with areaIndians prompted leaders to establish a trading post at the head of navigation on the Red River near a village of Natchitoches Indians. Large-scale settlement began after the Louisiana Purchase turning the town into a flourishing river port and crossroads, giving rise to vast cotton kingdoms along the river. Planters built magnificent plantations down river and fine homes in town for social events. Eventually, however, the river changed it’s course, bypassing Natchitoches. What was once known as the Red River is now Cane River Lake, a 30-something mile body of water that runs from the city’s downtown historic district through Plantation Country.&lt;/p&gt;
Natchitoches, the original French Colony, also known as the "City of Lights," from the Christmas light festival that begins after Thanksgiving each year, retains its European flavor through its architecture, heritage and lifestyle. At it’s heart is the National Historic Landmark District, a 33 block area, the only one outside New Orleans. Front Street, a brick thoroughfare, faces the beautiful Cane River Lake, where restaurants and businesses with wrought iron balconies can be explored . Many historic homes,churches, Bed and Breakfast Inns and commercial structures can be seen as well offering a mixture of Queen Anne and Victorian architecture, along with Creole style cottages throughout the district.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Two well known businesses have been located in the Historic District for many years.&lt;br /&gt;
Kaffie-Frederick Mercantile, established 1863, is the oldest continuously operated business in Natchitoches and Lasyone’s Restaurant, serving famous Louisiana meat pies, since 1967.&lt;/p&gt;
Natchitoches can boast of two well known movies filmed in the town and local area.&lt;br /&gt;
"Steel Magnolias" starring Dolly Parton, Julia Roberts, Daryl Hannah, Shirley McLaine, Sally Field and Olympia Dukakis, filmed entirely in Natchitoches, released in 1989 , based on a true story and written by Robert Harling Jr. who is a native and resident of Natchitoches.&lt;br /&gt;
"Horse Soldiers" a well known film, starring John Wayne and William Holden among others and was released in 1959.
&lt;p&gt;The area has several beautiful plantations to visit. One, Melrose Plantation, has a wonderful, diverse and remarkable history dating back to 1742 with a woman that was born a slave, later owning Melrose, Marie Therese Coincoin. This plantation just calls to the travelers for a visit and tour.&lt;/p&gt;
There are other interesting and historic sites to enjoy in the area. Two examples are Ft. Jessup, whose first commander was Zachary Taylor, and Las Adaes, founded in 1717,one of the first missions in the area and immortalized in Longfellows "Evangeline", make great short excursions.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Natchitoches is located on I-49 between Alexandria and Shreveport, about 140 miles north of Lafayette off I-10 and 70 miles south of Shreveport off I-20.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache is a large camoed container with the series code in the lid, as well as a few goodies. Muggles are wide spread,especially on the weekends and holidays, so use stealth at your discretion. Parking is available, although it can be hard to find during peak hours on weekends and holidays.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" height="61"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;div align="center"&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;This Cacher is a United States Air Force Veteran and also a Proud Member of the MAGC:&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.militarycache.org"&gt;&lt;img src="http://the3defaus.clearwire.net/Cache%20Logos/MAGC/MAGC-AF-Web.gif" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>in the shade
lifeline #7135609806</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1193640249"><groundspeak:date>2023-09-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We are excited to announce that we now have a brand new Cache Across America - Louisiana cache! It is now published and ready to find. The master lists have all been updated and you can find the new cache here:

https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCADYN6_cache-across-america-louisiana</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1191805874"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Just an update, we do have a new CAA Louisiana owner who is in the process of publishing a new cache for LA. He has chosen a way cool location very indicative of Louisiana and  is awaiting site permission now. More details on location once permission has been received. Fingers crossed!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1185848270"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It's always sad to see an old Cache Across America cache go. Please stand by though, there is a new CAA Louisiana in the works and hope to have it online soon!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1185814123"><groundspeak:date>2023-08-05T09:11:59</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="182970">isht kinta</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Since the cache owner has not responded to my reviewer log  requesting the geocache be maintained, the geocache has been archived.

isht kinta 
Geocaching Volunteer Reviewer

</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1178456815"><groundspeak:date>2023-07-04T10:48:45</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="182970">isht kinta</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false"># Unresolved Cache Maintenance Issue #

----------

Hello Cache Owner

I was wondering what is the status of your geocache? It has been several weeks since I last noted that the cache needs maintenance.

Are you still planning on repairing or replacing it? 

* If so, please post a note to the cache page about its status. 
* If you do not plan on replacing the cache, please archive the cache yourself!

Per the [Geocaching Guidelines](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines) section on [Cache owner responsibilities](https://www.geocaching.com/play/guidelines#ownerresponsibility), maintenance issues with caches are expected to be addressed within 4 weeks.  

**I shall check back in a couple of weeks. If no action has been taken at that time I shall archive the geocache.**

isht kinta
Community Volunteer Reviewer</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="44.31495" lon="-69.771133"><time>2006-09-14T00:00:00</time><name>GCYAAP</name><desc>Cache Across America - Maine by Haffy, adopted by Kaching Karen</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCYAAP</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Maine</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="462761" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Maine</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Haffy, adopted by Kaching Karen</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="221450">Kaching Karen</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="53" inc="1">Park and grab</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="0">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Maine</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Be sure to check out the website for more info here:http://www.oldfortwestern.org/
&lt;p&gt;The Augusta Greenway trails are a great place to walk and get in a view of the Capitol Dome across the river and also a chance to see the Old Arsenal as well too.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Thanks and Enjoy!!!! Haffy&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Maine&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/78/Maine_state_flag.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Augusta&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Portland&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 39th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 40th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 23rd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Old Fort Western, built in 1754 and a National Historic Landmark, is America's oldest surviving wooden fort - a reminder of the great contest between cultures that dominated New England life 250 years ago.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The Fort was built by the Kennebec Proprietors, a Boston-based company seeking to settle the lands along the Kennebec River that had been granted to the Pilgrims more than a century earlier. The company and the Province of Massachusetts both were interested in expanding their influence in the area as part of an effort by Britain and her colonies to take final political control of North America and to sever what they saw as the ties between the Abenaki (Maine's Indians) and the French in Canada.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Built at the head of navigation on the river, Fort Western served as a fortified storehouse in support of Fort Halifax, located 17 miles north. Supplies were shipped via sloop and schooner from Boston as many as four times a year, unloaded at Fort Western, then taken by flat-bottomed boat, often against a strong river current, to Fort Halifax. James Howard's Company garrisoned the Fort and guarded the head of navigation on the Kennebec from 1754 to 1767. A Massachusetts provincial unit, the original garrison was made up of Captain Howard, his sons, and 15 other men, mostly of Scotch-Irish descent, who had first been stationed at Fort Richmond, also on the Kennebec River about 15 miles below Fort Western, then transferred to the storehouse when construction was completed in October.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Fort Western was never attacked directly. Private Edward Whalen, however, was captured in May, 1755, as he attempted to deliver dispatches to Fort Halifax. He spent four years in captivity, first among the Indians, then as a prisoner in France. He was exchanged in 1760. Other garrison members were fired upon as they returned a boat to Fort Halifax in 1757.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Protected behind its four-pound cannon, the garrison spent most of its time doing routine duty, including boat repair, cooking, baking, brewing, and getting wood, in addition to helping re-supply Fort Halifax.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Hostilities on the Kennebec came to a virtual end in 1760 following Wolfe's capture of Quebec but the garrison at Fort Western, though reduced in strength, stayed on station until late in 1767 to help maintain an English presence on the river. Finally, when the last of the garrison was discharged, Captain Howard madearrangements to acquire the Fort's buildings and surrounding lands.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Benedict Arnold used Fort Western as a staging point for his assault on Quebec in 1775 during the American Revolution He stayed in the area for a week or more as his bateaux were completed and supplies loaded. Some of Arnold's officers, including Daniel Morgan, Aaron Burr, and Henry Dearborn, lodged in the Fort's main house. But never again after 1767 would soldiers be stationed at Fort Western. Its future instead played out not in military terms but as civilian store and private residence. .&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>About 10 steps from the birdhouse. Near the trail.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363296944"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-24T15:44:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3809719">FlyingDonkeys</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It’s a DNF from me</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360479899"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-11T15:12:50</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55327295">CJames7676</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">It was little easy to find</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362062276"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-10T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5170980">astarandson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">In town visiting from Chicago. What better way to spend Mother's Day than to sight see in Maine. My first Cache Across America! 49 to go... TFTH/SL </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360179318"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T09:49:15</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="37812451">CD1314</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dropped a travel bug that originally came from the Czech Republic!  Hope it can catch a ride back 🐞✈️</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1358432096"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-01T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3485489">carmen9295</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 2/4 of our Maine geicaching road trip. 

Today we made it to Acadia, and picked up quite a few caches along the way. This was one of them!

Thanks for the cache. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="39.540283" lon="-77.62105"><time>2006-08-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCXM3E</name><desc>Cache Across America - Maryland by DaisyChain and FBS67</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXM3E</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Maryland</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="442355" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Maryland</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>DaisyChain and FBS67</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="153241">DaisyChain</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Large</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="0">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="2" inc="1">Access/parking fee</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="31" inc="1">Camping nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Maryland</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Welcome to Maryland! This cache has been approved by the MD DNR.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Maryland&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/a0/Flag_of_Maryland.svg/744px-Flag_of_Maryland.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Annapolis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Baltimore&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 42nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 19th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 7th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41" target="_blank"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7" target="_blank"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maryland" target="_blank"&gt;Maryland&lt;/a&gt; was the seventh state to ratify the United States Constitution, and is nicknamed the Old Line State and the Free State. Its history as a border state has led it to exhibit characteristics of both the Northern and Southern regions of the United States.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;For a small state, Maryland possesses a great variety of topography; hence its other nickname, "America in Miniature." It ranges from sandy dunes dotted with sea grass in the east, to low marshlands teeming with water moccasins and large bald cypress near the bay, to gently rolling hills of oak forest in the piedmont region, and mountain pine groves in the west.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cumberland_Valley" target="_blank"&gt;Cumberland Valley&lt;/a&gt; is a geographic region that lies between &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_of_South_Mountain" target="_blank"&gt;South Mountain&lt;/a&gt; and the Blue Ridge Mountains of central Pennsylvania and western Maryland, United States. The valley lies almost entirely within Cumberland and Franklin counties in Pennsylvania and Washington County, Maryland. South Mountain is the name given to the continuation of the Blue Ridge Mountains after they enter Maryland and extends into Pennsylvania. The Battle of South Mountain was an 1862 battle in the American Civil War fought near the southern end of the range. Elements of both armies moved from the Frederick area to the Antietam battlefield over the South Mountain. This area is rich with Civil War History.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Located in the &lt;a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Appalachian_Mountains" target="_blank"&gt;Appalachian Mountains&lt;/a&gt; , &lt;a href="http://www.dnr.state.md.us/publiclands/western/greenbrier.asp" target="_blank"&gt;Greenbrier&lt;/a&gt; is a multi-use park providing many kinds of recreation. The &lt;a href="http://www.nps.gov/appa/index.htm" target="_blank"&gt;Appalachian Trail&lt;/a&gt; passes near the park. The 42-acre man-made lake and beach draw many visitors who enjoy geocaching, swimming, canoeing, hiking, picnicking and nature study. There is a fee to enter the park if you want the short walk.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Day use&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;* Park open 8 a.m. to sunset.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;*Day Use Service Charges: Memorial Day Weekend-Labor Day - weekdays $3 per person, weekends/holidays $5 per person; Labor Day-Memorial Day Weekend $3 per vehicle; May and September weekends $3 per person. Out-of-state residents add $2 to all day use service charges.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;* Seniors and disabled persons with pass and children in car seats are free.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;* This park often fills up in the Summer. Be creative and look around for alternate parking. Makes the hike longer but well worth it.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364733301"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="391376">ArnoldCacheCrew</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this cache in great condition on this beautiful day. Would not recommend doing the off trail portion in flip flops though 🤣. TFTC. TNSL.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363526301"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T12:10:31</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="6839622">jonathansimon</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thx!  1st CAA ever!  Happy Memorial Day </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362958956"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3797805">mrahudson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We haven't been pursuing this series but we're driving by and stopped for it.  A little chilly but at least the rain stopped during our visit.  The dogs had a nice walk and we didn't see many other people despite it being a holiday weekend.  2nd find in the series.  Thanks for placing and maintaining!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362952477"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3791981">mrsahudson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">On our way to New York and stopped to grab this one along the way. Took the dogs for a walk with us. Thanks</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363343245"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="25469328">Missbderycke</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Phone in Airplane Mode, Work Phone &amp; Laptop Shut Off, 5 days. 4 New States. 5 CAAs, 4 Cache Odysseys, 3000+ km driving, 25+km on foot, a lifetime of laughs &amp; memories = priceless.

Here is a short story long... in booking a hotel in November of 2025 I was asked to stay on the line and listen to an offer. While listening I was getting ready to head out on a hike with a friend so Im not going to lie I was paying zero attention. Afterward the lady was like does that sound good and I answered yes which prompted her to ask for my credit card number. Still not paying attention to what was going on and thinking I was paying for the November hotel I ended up with a 3 night 4 day stay to 11 different locations in the US for a really good deal. When I saw the email stating what I had just signed up for I called lindsayasdnil and said well I did this thing so pick from these 11 locations and we will go on a geotrip! She ended up deciding on Williamsburg, VA as it was one we could drive to and the closest-ish one. Now just to decide when we would go. We seem to like to road trip in May so we decided on doing that again and combine it with a milestone birthday for her. Since my goal is to visit all of the states and also complete this series while doing so we chatted about tacking on an extra day and visiting Delaware as neither of us had it as a state we were planning on visiting for a specific reason (but boy am I sure glad we did, more on this later). About a week before leaving I convinced her that we werent far from the New Jersey CAA either and we would be driving super close to the North Carolina border so we might as well pop down there for a hot minute and grab a cache as well.

This was day #5 of our adventures and our road trip to home. We left the hotel at 7am this morning and won't end up getting home until 10:30pm due to a few stops &amp; some traffic. This marks CAA#12 and the final cache of our trip. Nice little jaunt around the pond once we finally made it into the park (we weren't expecting a line up on a Monday mid afternoon however, it is really hot so that must be why). Also wasn't expecting that hill. Lindsayasdnil decided to take a little break when I realized she was essentially sitting on the cache. Signed up in, recorded the code and took the photo. Adding a fav point. Tftc! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.106633" lon="-72.688417"><time>2006-07-10T00:00:00</time><name>GCX2RH</name><desc>Cache Across America - Massachusetts by geogerry36</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX2RH</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Massachusetts</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="425711" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Massachusetts</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>geogerry36</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="2236511">GeoGerry36</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="0">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="58" inc="1">Fuel nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Massachusetts</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;This cache is between MA Route 20 and the Westfield River. It is practically a drive-up cache with plenty of empty parking spaces nearby. &lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="#FF0000"&gt;You do not need to cross the river to locate the cache!&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is a little hiking involved down the steep trail towards the riverbank. You will not feel uncomfortable at this spot because it is part of a recognized hiking trail.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Massachusetts&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/user/baab036c-abc8-4e01-ab2b-ac40811629e1.jpg" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Boston&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Boston&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 44th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 13th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 6th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capital upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;You'll find this cache where a historical trail and a nature trail collide. The historical trail recounts one of the most romantic episodes of the Revolutionary War, in which Henry Knox, a twenty-five year old Boston bookseller, organized and led the transport of fifty-nine captured artillery pieces, in the dead of winter, from Fort Ticonderoga to General George Washington's army outside Boston.&lt;/p&gt;
On July 3, 1775, Washington took command of the troops surrounding British-occupied Boston, urgently needing powder and other supplies. Washington asked Knox for his opinion on what the army should do and Knox's thought was to use the cannons from the captured Fort Ticonderoga in upstate New York. &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.nysm.nysed.gov/services/KnoxTrail/ktsign01.html"&gt;The Knox Trail - Sign Number 1&lt;/a&gt; Thus, Knox was commissioned a Colonel, placed in charge of artillery, and given the task to bring the cannons from Ticonderoga to Boston. By way of ox sleds, Knox successfully brought over fifty cannons to the city. Early in March 1776, using these cannons, Washington seized and occupied Dorchester Heights(the key to Boston), effectively commanding the city and forcing the British to evacuate on March 17, 1776. Boston&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=cb629e4c-4365-4ff4-9254-f45b00faf45e"&gt;(GCHJD6) Wayland 6.0 - Center of the Universe&lt;/a&gt; was entered the following day by triumphant Americans. The transportation of these cannons by oxen was very difficult over the muddy and snowy terrain, but Knox persevered and enabled one of the first major victories of the Revolutionary War. &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=105d3f52-a687-4f5b-baca-208cb6207c78"&gt;(GCG0XR) Victory Cache&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The Knox Trail &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.nysm.nysed.gov/services/KnoxTrail/images/knoxtrailmap.gif"&gt;(shown here)&lt;/a&gt; can be followed thanks to many dedicated historians and government officials who conceived and carried out the installation of 56 monuments across two states neary three-quarters of a century ago representing one of the earliest heritage trails created in the United States.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The nature trail is the Metacomet-Monadnock (M-M) Trail &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://amcberkshire.org/trails/mmtrail"&gt;(info)&lt;/a&gt;, which is a long distance hiking footpath, maintained by the Appalachian Mountain Club-Berkshire Chapter Trails Committee and other volunteers. It is approximately 114 miles from the blue-blazed Metacomet Trail on the Connecticut state line &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=a663ab54-3373-4975-98a9-97b48cc74044"&gt;(GC220D) Metacomet - Suffield, CT&lt;/a&gt; to Mt. Monadnock in New Hampshire.&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=b4597d51-05e1-41ec-b478-0bb164f07018"&gt;(GC4B19) Mt Monadnock&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
The M-M trail was originally laid out by the late Prof. Walter M. Banfield of the University of Massachusetts (our alma mater- GO UMASS &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=4a0bfd31-c826-4477-8a05-9191b46b2a59"&gt;(GCWQ61) UMass Tour #1&lt;/a&gt;) starting in the late 1950s, and has been evolving ever since. It passes through some of the prettiest landscape in Western Massachusetts, including the Mt. Tom State Reservation &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=cc501feb-46b3-4d77-8297-9014ac19b722"&gt;(GC9288) Mt. Tom Summit House Cache&lt;/a&gt;, Mt Holyoke Range &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=125bfd36-6b92-481f-bc89-cd2fd1f22aa2"&gt;(GCW825) 7 Wonderful women series//// Allison&lt;/a&gt;, and Skinner State Parks &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=ce1961c4-cde6-4f67-9844-401fa20f77b1"&gt;(GCP3G8) Connecticut River Oxbow in Northampton Earthcache&lt;/a&gt;, and numerous other state, municipal, and land trust properties. Today, over half of its length crosses public lands. The trail is marked or "blazed" with white painted rectangles on trees and rocks and supplemental white, metal, diamond-shaped signs affixed to trees and poles at road crossings and other trail intersections.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
Lesson Learned from this Cache - There's alot of history and beautiful countryside throughout the heartland of Massachusetts en route to our well-known capital, Boston!&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;font color="blue"&gt;Congratulations to Alberio &amp;amp; JugglerofDooom for being this cache's FTF, which scored them the highly coveted GCX2RH FTF Poker Chip! Thanks, too, for freeing the All American Smurf, so he can start out on his quest throughout America.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;The original contents of the cache include: one FTF poker chip token, an American Flag T-Shirt(Sz: L), four pins(2006 geocaching ammo can(2), flag, &amp;amp; patriotic ribbon), one Black Squirrel Postcard, one packaged emergency poncho, a twin pack of American Flag luggage tags, a vinyl zippered organizer, a Red Sox wristband, a pair of linesmen pliers, a paint brush, an American Kids lip balm with zipper pull, a pair of blue socks, the All American Smurf Travel Bug, and a logbook with pens (Black &amp;amp; Red, of course - Go BOMBERS!).&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Trailhead is in right-hand corner of parking lot.   Cache is at the base of a  large tree.   You DO NOT have to go down hill to retrieve the cache.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1007047996"><groundspeak:date>2021-04-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2236511">GeoGerry36</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">New CCA MA is GC98G7V located in Concord, MA.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1007047935"><groundspeak:date>2021-04-08T00:41:36</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2236511">GeoGerry36</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This CAA MA cache has been archived so that a new CAA MA could be placed in a very historic area of Massachusetts, and in fact of the Nation - Concord, MA.   I'm sorry if anyone unsuspecting of the relocation headed this way looking for the cache.   My apologies if that happened.   If so, please jump back into your cachemobile and head for the newer, much better location.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1003891804"><groundspeak:date>2021-03-29T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2236511">GeoGerry36</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">A word of caution to seekers of this cache.   I am in the process of moving it to a much safer and more historic location in the town of Concord, MA.   This move should only take a few days, so if you're headed to this cache here in Springfield, please check this cache page to be sure it hasn't been moved before you head out for it.   I'm sorry if this inconveniences anyone, but the move is long overdue.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1000745816"><groundspeak:date>2021-03-16T22:44:38</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="29915147">ACalandrella</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">:-( sadface. It was super cold maybe I didn’t look hard enough.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="999526190"><groundspeak:date>2021-03-10T17:18:01</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="17632871">Rcorriveau13</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Could not find </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.0516" lon="-84.410783"><time>2006-08-07T00:00:00</time><name>GCXK0G</name><desc>Cache Across America -Michigan by Team Rod &amp; Tod w/KAboom...The Cachestalkers</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXK0G</url><urlname>Cache Across America -Michigan</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="441303" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America -Michigan</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Team Rod &amp; Tod w/KAboom...The Cachestalkers</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="571405">Rockin Roddy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="0">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="35" inc="0">Off-road vehicles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Michigan</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Michigan&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/7/73/Michigan_state_flag.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Lansing&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Detroit&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 11th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 8th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 26th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Welcome to this great Team
Rod &amp;amp; Tod cache. This peaceful park, nestled in the middle of
Somerset, has many great features...the bridges, made of cement,
look like wooden bridges, there are fish in the eastern cement
pool. The two cement "trees" are chimneys for the building in the
hillside. Rumor has it that this area was once used by Al Capone
while on his travels between Chicago &amp;amp; Detroit! Also, this park
was recently listed as one of the most haunted parks in
America...keep an eye out for the previous inhabitants!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Bring a picnic and the family, there are grills available on
site, as well as a nice covered picnic area and a playground....a
baseball diamond is located just to the north of the area. Read the
historic plaque (which is also a virtual cache...W.H.L cache) and
search for another cache hidden somewhere in this park (Somerset's
Hauntings...hidden by Tod, Kaleb and myself as well). There are
also a series of letterboxes hidden throughout this park...happy
hunting!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Just to the southwest of this area is the beautiful Somerset
State Game Area...a 600+ acre rustic park mainly used for hunting,
has the scenic Lake Lombard in the center. There is a great scenic
trail which circles the large lake...this 4 mile trail takes you
through many great geological features, the lakes have some great
fishing...not easily accessible by boat though...sorry! MIS,
Stagecoach Stop, Walter J. Hayes State Park, Hidden Lake Gardens,
and Mystery Hill are just a few other attractions located in and
around the beautiful Irish Hills to the east. Even U.S. 12 is
historic...this road was once a main east-west stagecoach route, as
well as the main smuggling route for some notorious gangster like
Capone. Many nearby caches also await you!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Come enjoy this great area, spend some time in the beautiful
state of Michigan...we are glad you came!!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;a rel="nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/profile/?guid=3593b94e-1851-4fb1-ac91-8cd7a3732788"
   target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src=
   "http://img.geocaching.com/stats/img.aspx?txt=The+Cachestalkers&amp;amp;uid=3593b94e-1851-4fb1-ac91-8cd7a3732788&amp;amp;bg=2"
     border="0" title="Profile for Rockin Roddy" alt=
     "Profile for Rockin Roddy"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;center&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.mi-geocaching.org"
target="top"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://www.mi-geocaching.org/modules/Promote_MiGO/inb_image.php"
border="0"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/center&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Fallen</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="88094429"><groundspeak:date>2009-06-30T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="143223">itzme</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">#1836
Logging (10-21-09) for Recognition on INATN -- Found replacement GC1KHE3 6-30-09 
