14 Amarillo TX</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354305678"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-08T18:41:28</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1567152">HikingSeal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This ended up being my last find of the day. It was one of the primary targets of this trip interesting choice for the placement. The old Utah CAA was also placed in a central location, but access was much easier as it was right next to the interstate. This is definitely out in the boondocks. New Mexico is also a diverse state. My very first trip to NM was helping a friend who just graduated from college drive to LA for her first job. We just drove across. The first time I spent any time here was a business trip to Farmington. I saw Shiprock on that trip. I think I’ve  now visited all the big attractions in NM, including this cache. 😀

Thanks for the cache!

Found with [Cachly](https://www.cach.ly/)</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1349070620"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="282126">Cornflakes</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">This was one of our main caching goals on our ten-day trip to New Mexico, as we chip away at this challenge. This was CAA #27 for us. No trouble finding the cache in this deserted spot. It's hard to choose a favorite NM view for the second photo--so many lovely places. Thanks for the cache and greetings from Vermont!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1347546699"><groundspeak:date>2026-03-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="115013">SLOlocals</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Caching with Cornflakes, our sister and brother-in-law, who are collecting all of these.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1346351291"><groundspeak:date>2026-02-25T13:20:39</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="1280277">Tycoon Otto</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We’re down from Kelowna, British Columbia Canada, enjoying some warmer weather with our Caching buddies Londonwesty, lyriclass, Mr. and Mrs. Reidmylips and my amazing wife.😃
Thanks for putting out this series, slowly picking away at it.
Thanks for your hide and my new smile.😃
Signed in as CAN 6
Fave💪</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.95675" lon="-78.913283"><time>2006-08-06T00:00:00</time><name>GCXJ03</name><desc>Cache Across America  New York by Rayman</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXJ03</url><urlname>Cache Across America  New York</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="440329" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America  New York</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Rayman</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="300814">Rayman</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="42" inc="1">Needs maintenance</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="40" inc="1">Stealth required</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="26" inc="1">Public transportation nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>New York</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;New York&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/user/fce4e217-9310-4447-a733-2242f74860d4.jpg" width="180" height="90" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Albany&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: New York&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 27th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 3rd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 11th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; This cache is hidden along the Niagara River, on the Buffalo city line. You may notice the area you are in is lower than the road across the highway. That is because this used to be part of the Erie Canal when it used to continue to downtown Buffalo. This 9-mile section of the canal built in 1825 was described as "remarkably beautiful, having been laid out with great taste and judgement, and faithfully executed." Mules and horses pulled the barges through this section to avoid the current of the Niagara River. With the advent of mechanical power and the completion of the Barge Canal in 1918, the section between Buffalo and Tonawanda was abandoned. Across the river is Fort Erie, Ontario, and just 14 miles downtstream is Niagara Falls. The cache is just off a paved bike path, providing many scenic views.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Under the flowers between two smaller boulders</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="889730839"><groundspeak:date>2019-10-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Dear Cache Across America players:  Archiving a Cache Across America cache is always a sad day for us on the management team, and it is always our very last resort as we do everything possible to keep the old ones up and running. We would like to thank Rayman for his many years of hard work for maintaining the CAA NY cache over the years. The new Cache Across America New York cache has been published: GC8EHW7 and is in the Albany area. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="889518238"><groundspeak:date>2019-10-20T06:09:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="222509">New York Admin</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Regrettably there has been no response from the cache owner placing me in a position where I must archive this cache.  Caches archived by a reviewer or HQ staff for lack of maintenance or failure to respond can not be unarchived.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="887182377"><groundspeak:date>2019-10-07T23:00:44</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10691557">Swagwags</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thought I would try to find it on the off chance that it could have been replaced but not activated yet.  My search did not turn up anything.  Major bummer!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="884611671"><groundspeak:date>2019-09-24T22:49:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3111007">10000Steps</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Bummer... We live in the Chicago area and we are traveling to Buffalo this weekend. Disappointed that the cache is disabled. </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="884561918"><groundspeak:date>2019-09-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="92562">~Bailey~</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Made a special trip for this cache from Central MA. (Four and a half hours.)  Hoped that it may have been misplaced under another boulder as so many CCs tend to drift. Did not have the reviewers posting until after walking up and over the bridge in the hot sun for nothing.   This is such a disappointment as we are working on Cache Across America.  We needed the code of course.  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="36.5044" lon="-79.759767"><time>2006-08-02T00:00:00</time><name>GCXFVV</name><desc>Cache across America: North Carolina by erikwillke</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXFVV</url><urlname>Cache across America: North Carolina</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="438275" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache across America: North Carolina</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>erikwillke</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="302967">erikwillke</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="0">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="0">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="11" inc="1">May require wading</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="1">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="21" inc="1">Cliff/falling rocks</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>3.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Carolina</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;North Carolina&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://www.lawsource.com/also/flags/flag33nc.gif"
width="187" height="135" /&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Raleigh&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Charlotte&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 28th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 11th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 12th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;!--pictures--&gt;
&lt;!--end pictures--&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series
&lt;a rel="nofollow"
href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;
&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to
&lt;a rel="nofollow"
href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
This cache will take you to a hidden waterfall in Eden, North
Carolina.&lt;br /&gt;
My family and I found this little hideaway while investigating an
interesting but lifeless park. I've only lived here for a short
time but my co-workers who grew up here have never heard of this
waterfall. Morehead Park is the site of an old cotton mill that is
long-since gone. The stone foundation still remains and almost
looks like a quary from the road. To access the cache you will need
to actually enter from inside the foundation which is part of the
park. &lt;strong&gt;&lt;big&gt;Do Not&lt;/big&gt; Attempt This Cache From Any Other
Direction!&lt;/strong&gt; Not only is the surrounding area private&lt;br /&gt;
property but serious injury is likely.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here are my recommendations:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
1. Wear shorts and shoes with good traction. You&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;WILL&lt;/strong&gt; be crossing water and getting your lower legs
wet. There is NO way around it.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
2. Seal everything in ziplok bags or other waterproof containers or
leave it on the shore. Did I mention you &lt;strong&gt;WILL&lt;/strong&gt; get
wet?&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
3. Bring a walking stick, or better yet, bring 2. You will be
stepping on loose river stone, some of which you cannot see.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
4. Bring a camera. This site is absolutely beautiful.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;My Warnings:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
1. &lt;strong&gt;Do Not&lt;/strong&gt; try to access cache from opposite bank
or accross bridge as stated before. You will VERY likely get
seriously hurt and ruin your day.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
2. &lt;strong&gt;Do Not&lt;/strong&gt; attempt this cache after a hard rain. It
is a waterfall. You can imagine the rest. Don't worry. You'll know
right away if you should not do it. Average depth is no more than
calf in most spots and knees if you pick your route poorly. Any
higher than that I wouldn't do it.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
3. Closely supervise your children. I let my kids play here but I
am watching them like a hawk. They love it here.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
4. I would not attempt this at night. I have seen evidence of
transients and other partiers but I have not seen them in person
during the day.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;big&gt;&lt;big&gt;&lt;strong&gt;WARNING&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/big&gt;: This is a real world
cache with real world dangers. When you are at Ground Zero you will
plainly see the cache. You WILL NOT have to dig through the hiding
material to find it. Doing so will put you at GREAT risk. If you do
not see the container without moving hiding material then the cache
is not there or is not accessable. Use the last clue as a lifeline
to determine if it is still there.&lt;/big&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;div style="width:600;text-align:left"&gt;
