   target="_blank"&gt;View Slideshow&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Jneavat, gurfr ner gehr fcbvyref.

1. Just like Cache in the Bank.  

2. halfway up the rocks in the valley

3. Clear tupperware.  

4. lifeline- threethreesix-fiveeightnine-sixsixsixfour</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="125976735"><groundspeak:date>2010-09-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="684840">mujonny</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Here is the link to the replacement CAA for North Carolina, in case anyone else still has the old one bookmarked like I did. GC26AF5 - http://www.geocaching.com/seek/cache_details.aspx?guid=e5452ced-1ac5-4285-b4b2-12360019ee95</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="95599403"><groundspeak:date>2010-01-20T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="302967">erikwillke</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The cache is not available at this time.  There has been interest by another local cacher to place this one in Reidsville NC or somewhere closeby.  Please check back for more information.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="95581743"><groundspeak:date>2010-01-19T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="235743">FullTimeRVers</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">We're planning to be in NC next November.  Will the new one be ready by then?  What's the hold up?  At least, PLEASE submit an update notification here.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="93812882"><groundspeak:date>2009-12-28T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="989757">mblatch</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Rats!!  I was hoping to go do this one while I was in North Carolina over the holidays?   Is anyone going hide a new one for NC?  I probably won't be back here until next December now.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="92460733"><groundspeak:date>2009-12-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2745546">Gaijin Cacher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Any words on the new one?  We're visiting NC in DEC and would love to log this one!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.358167" lon="-80.8246"><time>2010-04-27T00:00:00</time><name>GC26AF5</name><desc>Cache Across America - North Carolina by TermiteHunter </desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC26AF5</url><urlname>Cache Across America - North Carolina</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="1624748" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - North Carolina</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>TermiteHunter </groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="1268246">TermiteHunter</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="55" inc="1">Short hike (&lt;1 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="14" inc="0">Recommended at night</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="63" inc="1">Recommended for tourists</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="15" inc="1">Available in winter</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Carolina</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>&lt;b&gt; DO NOT ENTER THE AMAZON FACILITY PARKING&lt;/b&gt; There is a park entrance near the intersection of Independence Hill and Old Statesville.
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;b&gt;Voted #1 Historical Analysis category for 2010 by the GCGC &lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.charlottegeocaching.com"&gt;&lt;img src="https://s3.amazonaws.com/gs-geo-images/7b300835-8ec0-466f-86da-48c8068b1caf.png" border="0" alt="Greater Charlotte Geocaching Club" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;b&gt;This cache is located near a monument to the signers of the Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence, May 20, 1775, and homesite of John McNitt Alexander, secretary of the committee that drew the Mecklenburg Declaration and the Mecklenburg Resolves before the American Revolution.   The dates of the Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence (May 20, 1775) and of the Halifax Resolves (April 12, 1776) are emblazoned on the state flag with the MeckDec date remaining since inception&lt;/b&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Mecklenburg County was among the first of the “back country” counties of the Colony of North Carolina. The general area was first settled in the 1740s, and Mecklenburg County was formed out of Anson County in 1762. The principle city of Mecklenburg County is Charlotte, founded in 1769. Today Charlotte is the largest city in the two Carolinas, but it was a small country village up to the time of the Civil War. The county and city were named in honor of Princess Charlotte of Mecklenburg-Strelitz, the new bride of King George III of England. Although Charlotte was not a large or important town during the early years, some interesting things happened here. Mecklenburg was the first government body in America to declare independence from the Crown of England, on May 20, 1775. This document was the famed Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence. Lord Cornwallis came to Charlotte in the fall of 1780 on his way to destroy the Continental Army, but he only stayed ten days. The local partisans were just too hot for him, and he later referred to Charlotte as &lt;b&gt;“A Hornet’s Nest of Rebellion”&lt;/b&gt; giving rise to Charlotte being called the Hornet’s Nest City today. Mecklenburg County was the center of America’s first gold rush, from 1799 to 1860. The first US Branch Mint was built in Charlotte in 1837 and minted gold coins until the outbreak of the Civil War. Near the end of the Civil War the Confederate Naval Yard was relocated here from Norfolk, Virginia because of the railroads that ran through here. During the First World War there was a large training camp here, Camp Greene. During World War Two Charlotte hosted a Army Airforce training camp at Morris Field. Today Charlotte is the second largest financial center in the US.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td valign="top" width="70%"&gt;
&lt;div class="UserSuppliedContent"&gt;
&lt;table border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2" width="76%"&gt;
&lt;tbody&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#999966" rowspan="4" width="190" align="middle"&gt;North Carolina
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Raleigh&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Charlotte&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank:22nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank:10th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 12th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41" rel="nofollow"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" height="48" valign="center" width="693" align="middle"&gt;
&lt;h1&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7" rel="nofollow"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" height="61"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt;The Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence is allegedly the first declaration of independence made in the Thirteen Colonies during the American Revolution. It was supposedly signed on May 20, 1775, at Charlotte, North Carolina, by a committee of citizens of Mecklenburg County, who declared independence from Great Britain after hearing of the battle of Lexington. If the story is true, the Mecklenburg Declaration preceded the United States Declaration of Independence by more than a year. The authenticity of the Mecklenburg Declaration has been disputed since it was first published in 1819, forty-four years after it was reputedly written.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;There is no conclusive evidence to confirm the original document's existence, and no reference to it has been found in extant newspapers from 1775. The flag of North Carolina bears the date of the Mecklenburg Declaration: May 20, 1775.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Many professional historians have maintained that the Mecklenburg Declaration of Independence is an inaccurate rendering of an authentic document known as the Mecklenburg Resolves. The Mecklenburg Resolves were a set of radical resolutions passed on May 31, 1775, that fell short of an actual declaration of independence. Although published in newspapers in 1775, the text of the Mecklenburg Resolves was lost after the American Revolution and not rediscovered until 1838.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Historians believe that the Mecklenburg Declaration was written in 1800 in an attempt to recreate the Mecklenburg Resolves from memory. According to this theory, the author of the Mecklenburg Declaration mistakenly believed that the Resolves had been a declaration of independence, and so he recreated the Resolves with language borrowed from the United States Declaration of Independence. Defenders of the Mecklenburg Declaration have argued that both the Mecklenburg Declaration and the Mecklenburg Resolves are authentic. The early government of North Carolina, convinced that the Mecklenburg Declaration was genuine, maintained that North Carolinians were the first Americans to declare independence from Great Britain. As a result, both the seal and the flag of North Carolina bear the date of the declaration.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A holiday commemorating the Mecklenburg Declaration, "Meck Dec Day", is celebrated on May 20 in North Carolina, although it is no longer an official holiday and does not attract the attention that it once did.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;We would like to thank Yuttington for his sacrifice in providing this location for the Cache Across America - North Carolina.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#CCCCCC" height="61"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt; &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td valign="top" width="10%"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1363892555"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-27T12:09:22</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3100031">Team Michtana</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Tftc, another code to add to the growing list.  </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1362499977"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-21T14:09:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="10595118">SandySoul</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">3/50. Getting there!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364715921"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-18T13:50:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="35451479">naturelvr59</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Sweetbeamie and I, along with our Geopup Little Bear are headed to GeoWoodstock 2026! Our second GeoWoodstock. 
 We spent May 17th to May 24th traveling from our home in Elkhart Indiana through OH, KY, TN, NC, SC, GA, FL, LA, MS, AR, MO, KS, NE, IA, IL. 
 So many goals checked off and so many cool caches along the way. Including GC30 MINGO. Thanks to every geocacher that puts out and maintains caches for us all to enjoy in our adventures across this great country.   TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1360046233"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-09T15:58:53</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="36663512">evandonge</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1359259603"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-04T20:34:03</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="48463028">ids123gb</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">great find! just a tip for future cashers, dont attempt at night.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="47.890833" lon="-97.020333"><time>2006-10-28T00:00:00</time><name>GCZ35R</name><desc>Cache Across America - North Dakota by adjensen</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCZ35R</url><urlname>Cache Across America - North Dakota</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="485672" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - North Dakota</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>adjensen</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="940464">PrairieGirl &amp; GeoDogBuddy</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="41" inc="1">Stroller accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="9" inc="1">Significant hike</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="62" inc="1">Seasonal access</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>3</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>North Dakota</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>Cache is a larger size aspirin bottle with natural camouflage. </groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;North Dakota&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/ee/Flag_of_North_Dakota.svg" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Bismarck&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Fargo&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 19th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 47th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 39th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; There is nothing that defines North Dakota more than its natural environment. Even our urban areas can embrace the harsh nature of living on the northern plains. Patti and I debated a number of different locations for this cache before settling on the Grand Forks Greenway, which exemplifies the region, both historical and environmental, while still remaining reasonably accessable most of the year.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In April, 1997, the Red River of the North overflowed its banks and flooded much of the town of Grand Forks. The flood drew worldwide attention, particularly when, paradoxically, a fire broke out in the downtown area, and fire fighters struggled to extinguish buildings that sat aflame, six feet deep in the river.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As with most disasters, the world moved on, but we in Grand Forks struggled with recovery. Despite predictions that the town would wither and die, it has indeed recovered, persevered, and even grown. This cache is hidden in one of the results of that recovery, the Grand Forks Greenway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;To the east of the cache, you will see the Red River, flowing north towards Lake Winnipeg and Hudson's Bay. Across the river, rich farmland is tilled in Minnesota, either sugar beets or potatoes, the two major crops grown in the Red River Valley. To the west, the hill you see is actually a dike, built by the Army Corps of Engineers, which protects the city from a flood of 61 feet.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In both 2006 and 2009, the efforts of the flood project proved their value. As communities up and down the valley fought the brave fight, aside from the bridges closing, and a few outlying areas not under protection needing sandbagging, Grand Forks was largely able to ignore the water. This freed up resources for helping out in Fargo, Oslo and other areas, but it really spoke to the benefits of flood prevention, rather than reaction. For a little perspective, during 2009, the cache location was under about four feet of water.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;North and south from here, the Greenway runs the length of the town, as both protection buffer and a recreational area. There are playgrounds, hiking, biking and ski paths, even a pretty big campground over on the east side. More information is at the &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.grandforksgov.com/greenway/index.htm" target="BLANK"&gt;Greenway web site&lt;/a&gt;. If you are coming from out of town to seek this cache, be sure to check out the many other finds along the Greenway.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;A couple of caveats. First, you will find parking at either Lincoln Park Golf Course, to the north, or on Elmwood Drive. Secondly, while there are a number of small game paths in, you &lt;u&gt;will&lt;/u&gt; encounter a lot of cockleburrs / thistles. Do not bring a dog in, or wear clothing that you don't want to be picking stuff out of for a long time. In spite of the urban location, this is a natural area, with all that entails.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Finally, in the winter, depending on how much snow is out there, you may need snowshoes to access the cache location. No complaining about the difficulty in finding during winter... this cache does represent North Dakota, after all &lt;img src="http://www.geocaching.com/images/icons/icon_smile.gif" border="0" align="middle" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;In the Fall of 2011, I moved out of state and have turned the cache over to its new owner. Thank you to all who came to visit our cache&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.handicaching.com/show.php?waypoint=GCZ35R" target="_blank"&gt;View Handicache rating for GCYKET&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
The cache location is not accessible by wheelchair. If you are doing the Cache Across America series, when you would like to log this cache, please contact me and we'll work out an alternative method.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;hr /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364644638"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T10:54:56</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="164089">jtee</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">very sneaky and well hidden..took awhile to get but we got it and signed in..thks for the fun </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364643861"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T10:52:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5660998">janjorjack</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I joined the WTF gang for another fun day of caching. We appreciate all the COs on the area placing these caches for us to find.  Thanks for the smile.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364756723"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T10:51:52</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="22496111">StonesFanInTO</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">2026 WTF Group Roadtrip of Manitoba; North Dakota &amp; Minnesota.

Day 4:  Grand Forks, ND

Spent the day in Grand Forks working on the Clues series; high favourites and assorted other targets.

Always happy to stop to get a cache in this series.  Wow - not expecting this hide.  Took 4 of us quite awhile to finally make the find and sign.

Signed SFIT 

TFTC
</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364725031"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T10:50:35</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="47235">capjap</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Day 3 of a road trip with WTF. Today we are in the Grand Forks area.  Wow this took us a while. Such good camo!  But it was right where we were looking. TFTC </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363780586"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T10:07:19</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="34793837">dynsph</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Took a fun little jaunt out into this beautiful country land. There is an absolutely massive farm. I did not know they could be that big. We spent way longer looking for this then we should’ve. Congrats on the devious camouflage. We’re heading back home now. I have come to really appreciate the beauty in this State. It was a good little trip. Thank you for placing this cache SL; TFTC PrairieGirl &amp; GeoDogBuddy!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.538" lon="-83.697217"><time>2006-09-10T00:00:00</time><name>GCY8FY</name><desc>Cache Across America – Ohio by JIMBOBWE</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCY8FY</url><urlname>Cache Across America – Ohio</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="461001" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America – Ohio</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>JIMBOBWE</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="451190">JIMBOBWE</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="0">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="28" inc="1">Public restrooms nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="27" inc="1">Drinking water nearby</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Ohio</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Ohio&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4c/Flag_of_Ohio.svg/480px-Flag_of_Ohio.svg.png"
     width="187" height="135"&gt; 
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Columbus&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Columbus&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 34th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 7th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 17th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle"
    bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
     width="450" height="221"&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to
   &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Ohio is located in
the Midwest and was the first state created out of the Northwest
Territory, which originally included all of modern-day Ohio,
Indiana, Illinois, and parts of Michigan and Wisconsin. The word
"Ohio" comes from the Iroquois Indian term "O-Y-O," which means
"the great river." Chillicothe was Ohio's original capital, but in
1816, the city of Columbus became the seat of government. The north
bank of the Ohio River defines Ohio's southern border. To the
north, Ohio is bordered by the state of Michigan and an
international boundary with Canada that passes through Lake Erie.
On the east, Pennsylvania and West Virginia neighbor the state,
with Indiana forming Ohio's western border. Ohio is approximately
355 kilometers across at its widest point. It is exactly the same
distance from its most southerly to its most northerly point. The
state encompasses 116,096 square kilometers of area. Land mass
comprises 106,054 square kilometers, with water making up the
additional 10,042 square kilometers. The state is shaped somewhat
like a heart. As a result, Ohio leaders often use the phrase "The
Heart of It All" to tout its business, educational, and
recreational opportunities. The highest point in the state is
Campbell Hill near Bellefontaine. It rises 1,549 feet above sea
level. The lowest point in the state is at the Ohio River near
Cincinnati, 455 feet above sea level. Within its boundaries, Ohio
enjoys some of the most fertile soil in the United States. Much of
that soil was deposited by a series of glaciers that advanced into
the area thousands of years ago. The most recent of these left the
region about thirteen thousand years ago. The glaciers also had a
major impact on the topography of Ohio, smoothing and flattening
the central and western areas of the state. Eastern Ohio, which was
untouched by the glaciers, features more rugged terrain marking the
foothills of the Appalachian Mountains. Another important
geographical feature in early Ohio was the Black Swamp located in
the northwestern part of the state. It originally consisted of
dense forests, and for much of the year, the land was flooded.
During the mid-nineteenth century, Ohioans drained the swamp. This
area now consists of some of the most fertile agricultural land in
the entire United States. During prehistoric times, American
Indians from several major traditions occupied the area. The
Paleoindian people were hunters and gatherers who entered the
region about 13,000 B.C. People of the Archaic tradition were also
hunters and gatherers who lived in the region from about 8000 B.C.
until 500 B.C. The Woodland tradition, which lasted from about 800
B.C. to A.D. 1200 introduced pottery, cultivated plants, settled
village life, and mound building to the region. Many of the mounds
and earthworks created by various cultures of the Woodland
tradition are now preserved as prehistoric treasures within the
state. Perhaps the most famous of these is Serpent Mound in Adams
County. The last prehistoric people to occupy the region were
members of the Late Prehistoric tradition. These people, who lived
in large villages surrounded by farms, lived in the area from about
A.D. 1000 to 1650. French explorers in search of furs first came to
the area now known as Ohio in the 1660s. They found a richly
forested area with abundant water and mineral resources and a
generally pleasant climate. Those same features later attracted
English settlers from the colonies on the Atlantic seaboard who
were more interested in farming and settling than fur trading. At
the same time that the region was attracting the interest of
Europeans, it was in the process of being re-settled by historic
Indian tribes including the Chippewa, Delaware, Eel River,
Iroquois, Kaskaskia, Miami, Mingo, Munsee, Ottawa, Piankashaw,
Potawatomi, Sauk, Seneca, Shawnee, Wea, and Wyandot. The English
colonists eventually established their dominance in the area with
victories in the French and Indian War and the Ohio Indian Wars.
Throughout the 19th and 20th centuries Ohioans reshaped the state's
landscape with networks of canals, railroads, and highways. During
the same period, Ohio's population swelled and the state developed
into a dominant economic and political force
nationally.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I picked this location because it's Historical significance in
OHIO and it's senic view.The Battle of Falen Timbers was fought
very close to these shores.This area is WORLD famous for Walleye
fishing as well.There are plenty of great geocaches in the area to
do.North West Ohio is a Geocachers Dream.We are loaded with every
kind of Geocache imaginable.Ammo cans to evil micro's!!So if you
geocache for numbers or for the senery you'll love this area.
Historical Fort Meigs is just minutes away.Downtown TOLEDO which
has Fifth Third Field,home of the MUD HENS.The beautiful Toledo ZOO
and the Toledo Art Museum is also just minutes away.There is so
much to do around here that i can't possibly name it
all.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>Below covered with stone</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="567238397"><groundspeak:date>2016-01-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15177653">ExpLaur</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Previously logged as GaxnLa and critln58 (now Gax2884).</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="314239957"><groundspeak:date>2013-05-14T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The new Cache Across America Ohio will be submitted for publication very soon.  It will be listed under GC4BPKP.  The Cache Across America bookmark will be updated upon publication and can be found at the following link:

http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41

Thank you everyone for your patience and understanding.  Maintaining the Cache Across America series is a difficult job to do and I have appreciated greatly your private emails of support.  The owner of the new Cache Across America Ohio has done a fantastic job of choosing a location and a theme that will do your great state of Ohio very proud.

Cache on!

Regards,

Lorriebird</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="314213038"><groundspeak:date>2013-05-14T03:26:09</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="7030713">The Brigadier</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Archived.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="312518654"><groundspeak:date>2013-05-08T13:53:14</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Needs Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Every so often an individual state Cache Across America cache has to be archived and re-created in a new cache.  This cache has had a fabulous run of over 6 years (!) and it was a favorite of many.  On behalf of Blue Power Rangers and Cache Across America cachers around the country, we sincerely thank JIMBOBWE for his years of effort and commitment.  After all, without the individual state caches, there would be no Cache Across America series!  This has been a great cache, I loved it back when I found it myself.

My apologies to the Cache Across America cachers who have been waiting for a resolution for Cache Across America Ohio.  We have been working towards a solution and are proud to announce that there is a brand new Ohio cache in the works and we hope to have it published and ready to go by the end of May!  We are very excited about the new location too, as it proudly represents the great state of Ohio and will be referencing the Birthplace of Aviation near Dayton Ohio! [^]

I will post a new GC number for Ohio CAA players asap.  In the meantime, here is a link to all the current CAA caches.  This list will be kept updated with all CAA caches, both past and present.  You may follow the link to my bookmark here:

  http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41

Thank everyone for your patience and we will get the new Cache Across America Ohio up and running as soon as possible!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="312542463"><groundspeak:date>2013-05-08T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5673269">issak</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">That's sucks. Its going to Dayton. Ok who wants to put a new one in the same spot? If no one wants to I'll do it!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.522883" lon="-98.782"><time>2006-07-29T00:00:00</time><name>GCXD60</name><desc>Cache Across America - Oklahoma by John52</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCXD60</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Oklahoma</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="435707" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Oklahoma</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>John52</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="93595">John52</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Oklahoma</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>br&amp;gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Oklahoma&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/2/26/Oklahoma_state_flag.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Oklahoma City&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Oklahoma City&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 20th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 27th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 46th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capitol upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; The cache is located in an area where the past meets the future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The cache has been placed within a few feet of historic Route 66. Once a major highway that moved travlers and goods from Chicago to LA. In Oklahoma it stretches from the Green Country in the Northeast to the Capitol City of Oklahoma City, then west through the wheat fields of Western Oklahoma. Affectionaly known as the Mother Road, Oklahoma has more miles of road-bed left than any other state. From the cache site look North or South and you can see a new energy source being harnessed. The Weatherford Wind Energy Center is one of the states largest wind farms. Located on 5,000 acres the 98 turbines produce up to 147 megawatts of electricity. That's enough to power more than 44,000 homes. This is a clean renewable source of power for the future. Take a short trip down Route 66 and see the windmills of the future.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&amp;lt;&amp;lt;p&amp;gt;
</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>footlong tube, bottom of utility pole</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364829278"><groundspeak:date>2026-06-01T09:49:57</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55537300">adventurepp</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for my first find! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363636985"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-23T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="8218630">itwasmymouse</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cache Across America!! 

Reminds me of Mingo, side of a field in the middle of no where! 

- - We're not in Ohio anymore! - -
Geowoodstock 2026 Adventure! 

Geocaching from Sylvania, Ohio. Caching and spending time with JenOvations, we used our joint stamp on most logs. We have the MOST fun together. 

This caching trip was one for the statistics book! Totally blessed to share these memories with this beautiful and wonderful woman. 

Trip details: 
- 5 days - 3,365 miles 
- 12 states (2 new geo states, OK, AR) 
- LOTS of new counties 
- 7 state capitals
- 450+ physical caches
- 125+ Larges (116 in a day)
- Lab arts (MO, GWXXII, KS. OK, AL)
- Lots of oldies: 2, 3 &amp; 4 digit GC's
- Oldest letterbox in USA/world
- 3 State's Oldest's: NE, OK, TN
- 6 Cache Across America Caches:
IL, NE, KS, OK, AR, MS
- 5 Geotour Cache Odyssey Caches:
MO, KS, NE, OK, AR
- 6 new event states
- 1 awesome drone show
- 1 MEGA &amp; 1 MAZE 

Cheapest Gas - $3.78 Decatur, AL
Expensive gas - $4.99 Wilmington, IL 

Thanks for adding to our Geowoodstock 2026 adventure and helping me with various goals, TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363878785"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="48318008">dobiest</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Another CAA under my belt. This was an easy find. TFTC SL </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363871661"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-22T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="2464712">Troopbiz</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">**Cache Across America - Oklahoma**
**Find #22099**
**Cache Across America #34**

**About This Cache**
I'm on a quest to finish the Cache Across America series, and despite only working on it for about 3 years now, I'm well over halfway through the states. It's a lot of traveling, but a fun way to explore new locations and see what different states have to offer. This was my first time in Oklahoma, so finding the CAA here was a must, and it just so happened to be directly south of Hutchinson, the home of GeoWoodstock XXII.

Really enjoyed traveling Route 66 on the way to this cache. I think this is the fourth or fifth segment I've been on during my various travels. A fitting location for this CAA hide and a nice container to boot. All is well here. TFTC SL

**About My Trip**
Traveling from Morgantown to Hutchinson to attend GeoWoodstock XXII, my 7th, with DOBIEST. We started our adventure in Tulsa and are looking forward to not only finding my first caches in Oklahoma, but also finding the oldest, Cache Across America, and Cache Odyssey, before heading north into Kansas. Lots of cool caching here, and we squeezed in as much as we could into a long travel day. Thanks, John52, for placing and maintaining this cache! All logs are signed “Troopbiz” or “TB”. TFTC SL</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364491249"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-20T18:05:02</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="5635701">jecepe08</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">I don't have many of these caches, so when I see one on my route...I'm stopping </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="42.897933" lon="-123.247433"><time>2006-07-09T00:00:00</time><name>GCX2F1</name><desc>Cache Across America - Oregon by Riddlers</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCX2F1</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Oregon</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="425416" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Oregon</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Riddlers</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="24" inc="0">Wheelchair accessible</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="17" inc="1">Poisonous plants</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Oregon</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description /><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Oregon&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src=
"http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/8/86/Oregon_state_flag.png"
width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Salem&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Portland&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 9th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 28th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 33rd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;
HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor=
"#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg"
width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a
series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire
United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These
caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel=
"nofollow" href=
"http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;
one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capital upon completion
of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; This location was known as
Canyon Creek Pass. This narrow gorge has long served as a travel
corridor. Native Americans likely trekked this canyon for thousands
of years. Alexander McLeod of the Hudson&amp;lsquo;s Bay Company
provided the first written account of the route in 1829 while
traveling from Fort Vancouver, on the Columbia River to
California&amp;lsquo;s Central Valley. In 1846 this route became part
of the Applegate trail, an alternative route to a bad portion of
the Oregon Trail. Stagecoaches followed this route in 1870s and
today, Interstate 5 connects Washington to California through these
steep passes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Within 100 miles of this point are many great areas. To the
northeast is Crater Lake, to the south is Ashland and the
Shakespearian festival. To the west is the ocean and some really
great beach caching.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache is hidden near a point of interest describing the
route. Parking is easy to get to from all directions. We had to
place this further from the parking as it has already disappeared
five times. Don't let the change in location stump you, it is close
by and there is no climbing required.p&amp;gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Be sure to get the numbers off the lid and take a picture if you
are going for all 50 states and the grand cache at the end. For all
others, just log this as a regular cache. TBs and trade items
welcome.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you
would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant
in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself
or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you
for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please
make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual
cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge
participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required
before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three
digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure
place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all
50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good
luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints>You can get close by keeping your feet on the road until you find the right tree.</groundspeak:encoded_hints><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="567238400"><groundspeak:date>2016-01-06T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="15177653">ExpLaur</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Previously logged as GaxnLa and critln58 (now Gax2884).</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="523595491"><groundspeak:date>2015-07-25T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Removing icon</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="499038604"><groundspeak:date>2015-05-05T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="748746">lorriebird</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Hello to all the watchers of this cache.

I am still getting emails about this cache that was archived a year ago today.  Please note that a new CAA Oregon was published in a very wonderful location.  Here is a link to a bookmark with all CAA caches, both past and present.

http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41

Hope this helps!

Lorriebird/Cache Across America</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="494664017"><groundspeak:date>2015-04-21T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="911809">MonkeyCacher</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Still no update in a YEAR? I've got a road trip through OR in a few weeks and would love to knock CAA #40 off my list :(</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="457956512"><groundspeak:date>2014-10-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3861097">dittocat</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Cool thanks.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="41.958383" lon="-75.661517"><time>2006-09-07T00:00:00</time><name>GCY6HQ</name><desc>Cache Across America – Pennsylvania by Jtd18801</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCY6HQ</url><urlname>Cache Across America – Pennsylvania</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="459135" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America – Pennsylvania</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>Jtd18801</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="195137">jtd18801</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes /><groundspeak:difficulty>2</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Pennsylvania</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
