&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.mtgc.org/"
target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src=
"http://www.mtgc.org/mtgc_member-banner.gif" alt=
"Member of Middle Tennessee GeoCachers Club - www.mtgc.org"
     width="500" height="40" border="0"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="41715723"><groundspeak:date>2008-04-02T08:14:54</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Archived</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="215950">salpal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Please see the new CCA-TN  (GC1AK40).  Thanks for all who hunted this one.  The new one has the same Code.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="40704033"><groundspeak:date>2008-03-17T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Write note</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="143949">CFD29</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Sure hope this one gets back up , planning trip thru here last week of March, was hoping to get the TN CAA</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="39942821"><groundspeak:date>2008-03-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="207334">geofreelance</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Salpal was a great help with this today since the real cache is temporarily out of commission. Since I had business in the area, we met up and did a "mock up" photo so I could get credit for another CAA. #4 of 50. tftc! Hope the new hiding spot works out soon.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="39350931"><groundspeak:date>2008-02-20T10:43:49</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Unknown</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="215950">salpal</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Once again, it's MIA.  I will be scouting out another locale for this cache, and buying another ammo can.</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="38474393"><groundspeak:date>2008-02-02T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Didn't find it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="409795">runningokra</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">this is easily observed area so I'm wondering if it is MIA again.  Gonna try again a bit later.   

Went back on a clear sunny day and had no luck at all.  There is a nail inside the trunk but nothing else.  If you happen to KNOW it is still there please post.  I seem to be off my game with only 1/3 this week.



[This entry was edited by runningokra on Friday, February 08, 2008 at 7:16:33 AM.]</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="35.8973333333333" lon="-87.0035833333334"><time>2008-03-26T00:00:00</time><name>GC1AK40</name><desc>Cache Across America - Tennessee by salpal</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GC1AK40</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Tennessee</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="828694" available="true" archived="false"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Tennessee</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>salpal</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="215950">salpal</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Regular</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="1" inc="1">Dogs</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="7" inc="1">Takes less than one hour</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="25" inc="1">Parking nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="32" inc="1">Bicycles</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="30" inc="1">Picnic tables nearby</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="18" inc="1">Dangerous animals</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="19" inc="1">Ticks</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="39" inc="1">Thorns</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>2</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Tennessee</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>The cache is located in a Williamson County Park, with paved road/trail to about 20 feet of the cache. Then you are on your own! Please rehide it well with local camouflage. The code is the same as the original CCA-TN.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Tennessee&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/9e/Flag_of_Tennessee.svg/800px-Flag_of_Tennessee.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Nashville&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Memphis&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 36th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 16th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 16th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=9bbb6655-e2ef-459b-80f6-66a9decd9d41" target="_blank"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=68e2d17a-8ae9-45c9-9516-0e45694cc2d7" target="_blank"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capital upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; Nashville is known for many things, including its universities and colleges, top-notch medical facilities and of course MUSIC!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;This cache is located near a small town in Middle Tennessee that is a treat in and of itself to visit. The following is excerpted from their website: http://www.leipersforkvillage.com&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Back in the old days, long before the early settlers arrived, the vast area around Leipers Fork was a communal hunting ground to an assortment of prehistoric American Indians who later evolved into tribes known today as the Cherokee, Chickasaw and Shawnee. Their presence in the area is marked by a seemingly endless supply of relics dating back some 4,000 years. Early settlers who came across the mountains from the east found a rich, fertile land but a harsh lifestyle in a strange and challenging wilderness. Because of the formidable environment containing both natural and man-made dangers, it was an ongoing struggle just to till the land, feed a family and reach old age. By 1795, certain adaptations had come to the frontier; a semblance of order prevailed for homesteaders while the Native Americans continued to reconcile to the changes the Europeans brought. The Leipers Fork area was settled in the late 1790s by pioneering families from North Carolina and Virginia that were given land grants as payment for their services in the Revolutionary War. The present village of Leipers Fork is situated on part of the 2,504 acre land grant of Col. Jesse Steed which was later purchased by Jesse Benton in 1801. Among the most famous settlers was Benton’s son, Thomas Hart Benton who later became a U.S. Senator from the state of Missouri, prominently influencing establishment of the West. Today, an historic marker honors the site of the Benton home. During the early days, travelers on the Natchez Trace who passed through the Benton homestead referred to the settlement as Bentontown. After a quarrel with General Andrew Jackson, which ended in a brawl and gun fight in a hotel in Nashville with Jackson seriously injured from a gunshot through the shoulder, the Bentons decided that Tennessee was not large enough for them and Jackson. They beat a hasty retreat to Missouri. The village was renamed Hillsboro as many of the early settlers, like the Bentons, were originally from Hillsborough, North Carolina. Logging Requirements: Enjoy this cache as you would any other.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td colspan="2"&gt; &lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;a rel="nofollow" href="http://www.mtgc.org/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.mtgc.org/mtgc_member-banner.gif" alt="Member of Middle Tennessee GeoCachers Club - www.mtgc.org" width="500" height="40" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Tennessee Capital: Nashville Largest City: Memphis Size Rank: 36th Population Rank: 16th Admission to Union: 16th   Find the other caches in the series HERE.   The Cache Across America Series: This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to one final cache located in our nation's capital upon completion of the series. About this cache: Nashville is known for many things, including its universities and colleges, top-notch medical facilities and of course MUSIC! This cache is located near a small town in Middle Tennessee that is a treat in and of itself to visit. The following is excerpted from their website: http://www.leipersforkvillage.com Back in the old days, long before the early settlers arrived, the vast area around Leipers Fork was a communal hunting ground to an assortment of prehistoric American Indians who later evolved into tribes known today as the Cherokee, Chickasaw and Shawnee. Their presence in the area is marked by a seemingly endless supply of relics dating back some 4,000 years. Early settlers who came across the mountains from the east found a rich, fertile land but a harsh lifestyle in a strange and challenging wilderness. Because of the formidable environment containing both natural and man-made dangers, it was an ongoing struggle just to till the land, feed a family and reach old age. By 1795, certain adaptations had come to the frontier; a semblance of order prevailed for homesteaders while the Native Americans continued to reconcile to the changes the Europeans brought. The Leipers Fork area was settled in the late 1790s by pioneering families from North Carolina and Virginia that were given land grants as payment for their services in the Revolutionary War. The present village of Leipers Fork is situated on part of the 2,504 acre land grant of Col. Jesse Steed which was later purchased by Jesse Benton in 1801. Among the most famous settlers was Benton’s son, Thomas Hart Benton who later became a U.S. Senator from the state of Missouri, prominently influencing establishment of the West. Today, an historic marker honors the site of the Benton home. During the early days, travelers on the Natchez Trace who passed through the Benton homestead referred to the settlement as Bentontown. After a quarrel with General Andrew Jackson, which ended in a brawl and gun fight in a hotel in Nashville with Jackson seriously injured from a gunshot through the shoulder, the Bentons decided that Tennessee was not large enough for them and Jackson. They beat a hasty retreat to Missouri. The village was renamed Hillsboro as many of the early settlers, like the Bentons, were originally from Hillsborough, North Carolina. Logging Requirements: Enjoy this cache as you would any other.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt;&lt;a href="http://www.mtgc.org/" target="_blank"&gt;&lt;img src="http://www.mtgc.org/mtgc_member-banner.gif" alt="Member of Middle Tennessee GeoCachers Club - www.mtgc.org" width="500" height="40" border="0" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

</groundspeak:long_description><groundspeak:encoded_hints /><groundspeak:logs><groundspeak:log id="1364725680"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3797805">mrahudson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">The overflow lot right next to the hide was closed so we had a little bit of a walk but it wasn't bad.  Took a couple tries to get a good approach and once we did we had the cache pretty quickly.  4th find in this series.  TFTC!</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1364720042"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-31T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="3791981">mrsahudson</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Took a little walk with the dogs to come get this one and got ink on the log. Thanks</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363611436"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T15:50:26</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="53295963">PepziePoe</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks 🥰 my first cache in USA 🥰</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1363611285"><groundspeak:date>2026-05-25T15:50:11</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="55483247">lyckster</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Thanks for my first find! </groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log><groundspeak:log id="1354404456"><groundspeak:date>2026-04-04T12:00:00</groundspeak:date><groundspeak:type>Found it</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:finder id="411445">Fink007</groundspeak:finder><groundspeak:text encoded="false">Found this morning with sjfink, RyanXY, and HayBeth during our visit to Nashville.  This redeemed a DNF for us way back in 2018, the last time we were in Nashville.

In this series, I am up to 36, sjfink is up to 35, and RyanXY and HayBeth are both up to 34. TFTC</groundspeak:text></groundspeak:log></groundspeak:logs></groundspeak:cache></wpt><wpt lat="32.2107" lon="-100.055583"><time>2006-07-04T00:00:00</time><name>GCWZ1F</name><desc>Cache Across America - Texas by AMMOMAN (adopted by Bigguy  In  Texas)</desc><url>https://www.geocaching.com/geocache/GCWZ1F</url><urlname>Cache Across America - Texas</urlname><sym>Geocache</sym><type>Geocache|Traditional Cache</type><groundspeak:cache id="422113" available="false" archived="true"><groundspeak:name>Cache Across America - Texas</groundspeak:name><groundspeak:placed_by>AMMOMAN (adopted by Bigguy  In  Texas)</groundspeak:placed_by><groundspeak:owner id="601992">Bigguy  In  Texas</groundspeak:owner><groundspeak:type>Traditional Cache</groundspeak:type><groundspeak:container>Small</groundspeak:container><groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:attribute id="6" inc="1">Recommended for kids</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="8" inc="1">Scenic view</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="13" inc="1">Available 24/7</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="56" inc="0">Medium hike (1 km–10 km)</groundspeak:attribute><groundspeak:attribute id="10" inc="0">Difficult climb</groundspeak:attribute></groundspeak:attributes><groundspeak:difficulty>1.5</groundspeak:difficulty><groundspeak:terrain>1.5</groundspeak:terrain><groundspeak:country>United States</groundspeak:country><groundspeak:state>Texas</groundspeak:state><groundspeak:short_description>About This Cache - This cache is located in Hutto Lake Park just off of Highway 130 near the Gatis School exit. The area is only about 20 miles from Austin (the capitol of Texas) and in a cache rich area. Come for the CAA-Tx cache and stay for all the other central Texas caching fun! The cache is large enough for plenty of swag and medium to large travelers.
</groundspeak:short_description><groundspeak:long_description>&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;table width="76%" border="0" cellspacing="4" cellpadding="2"&gt;
&lt;tr valign="top"&gt;
&lt;td width="190" rowspan="4" align="center" bgcolor="#999966"&gt;
&lt;h2 align="center"&gt;Texas&lt;/h2&gt;
&lt;img src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/f/f7/Flag_of_Texas.svg/800px-Flag_of_Texas.svg.png" width="187" height="135" /&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Capital: Austin&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Largest City: Houston&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Size Rank: 2nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Population Rank: 2nd&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Admission to Union: 28th&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="left"&gt;Find the other caches in the series &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=bf517972-5f45-4ed9-ac4b-afbde9231a6c"&gt;HERE&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p align="center"&gt; &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;td width="693" height="48" align="center" valign="middle" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;h1 align="center" class="style1"&gt;&lt;img src="http://img.geocaching.com/cache/166de36d-345c-48ac-a95b-898064ff2c2c.jpg" width="450" height="221" /&gt;&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td bgcolor="#99CC99"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;The Cache Across America Series:&lt;/strong&gt; This is a series of caches that will take you on a caching tour of the entire United States. One cache is hidden in each of the 50 states. These caches each contain a numeric clue that will lead you to &lt;a href="http://www.geocaching.com/bookmarks/view.aspx?guid=945ad12c-cf93-4d79-99ad-c3d727f767da"&gt;one final cache&lt;/a&gt; located in our nation's capital upon completion of the series.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;About this cache:&lt;/strong&gt; This cache is located near the Horse Hollow Wind Farm located about 20 miles South of Abilene.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;As you start driving toward this cache will start seeing these hugh "windmills". As of September 7, 2006 this farm is the largest in the world.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
&lt;/tr&gt;
&lt;tr&gt;
&lt;td height="61" bgcolor="#CCCCCC"&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Logging Requirements:&lt;/strong&gt; Enjoy this cache as you would any other. If you are searching this cache as a participant in the Cache Across America series, please post a photo of yourself or a member of your group with the cache in your online log. If you for some reason are unable to meet the photo requirement, please make alternate arrangements to verify your find with the individual cache owner. There is no photo requirement for non-challenge participants.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Individual verification of all 50 state finds will be required before logging the series final.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If participating in the series, please take note of the three digit code located inside this cache. Save this code in a secure place. When you have visited all 50 caches, and have collected all 50 codes, you are welcome to seek and find the final cache! Good luck!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/td&gt;
